Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_UART_ACK_TIMEOUT 0x01c4 uint16 250

Acknowledgement timeout for BCSP and H5

When the firmware sends a reliable message over BCSP or H5 it starts a timer. The timer's period is the value of this PSKey in milliseconds. If the host acknowledges reception of the message before the timer fires then the timer is cancelled. If the timer fires then the message is sent again and another timer started, etc.

You can limit the number of times a timer is used for a given reliable BCSP/H5 message using PSKEY_UART_TX_MAX_ATTEMPTS.

Note: The "H5" host transport protocol is properly known as the "Three-Wire UART Transport Layer", but is commonly known as H5 within CSR.

For more information see CSR document "BlueCore Serial Protocol (BCSP)", CS-101685-SP.

The sleep timeout configured in PSKEY_UART_SLEEP_TIMEOUT, if enabled, must be greater than the acknowledgement timeout configured in this PSKEY.

If the host wakeup mechanism is enabled with PSKEY_UART_HOST_WAKE, the Sleep_Delay configured in that PSKey must also be greater than the acknowledgement timeout configured here.

In builds from HCI 18.X, this key replaces PSKEY_UART_SEQ_TIMEOUT.


Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_UART_TX_MAX_ATTEMPTS 0x01c5 uint16 Default 0
Maximum 200

Max times to send reliable BCSP or H5 message

The description of PSKEY_UART_ACK_TIMEOUT outlines BCSP's mechanism to retransmit reliable messages to the host until acknowledged.

This PSKey sets a limit on the number of times the send/timeout cycle is attempted. If this limit is reached, the firmware panics and usually reboots.

Messages are sent indefinitely if this PSKey is set to zero, i.e., the value zero is treated as infinity.

This PSKey is also used with H5.

Note: The "H5" host transport protocol is properly known as the "Three-Wire UART Transport Layer", but is commonly known as H5 within CSR.

For more information see CSR document "BlueCore Serial Protocol (BCSP)", CS-101685-SP.

In builds from HCI 18.X, this key replaces PSKEY_UART_SEQ_RETRIES.


Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_UART_TX_WINDOW_SIZE 0x01c6 uint16 Default 4
Minimum 1
Maximum 6

Transmit window size for BCSP and H5

This PSKey holds the size of the sliding window used by BCSP.

When the baseband sends a reliable BCSP message to the host then the host is required to acknowledge its reception. If it is not acknowledged within a certain period the message is sent again.

The baseband sends several packets to the host before waiting for the first of the packets to be acknowledged. The maximum number of sent packets that can be unacknowledged at any time is set by this PSKey. When a packet is acknowledged, the next packet is sent. Under normal circumstances, the number of packets in transit to the peer is the value of PSKEY_UART_TX_WINDOW_SIZE.

This PSKey is also used with H5.

Note: The "H5" host transport protocol is properly known as the "Three-Wire UART Transport Layer", but is commonly known as H5 within CSR.

For more information see CSR document "BlueCore Serial Protocol (BCSP)", CS-101685-SP.

In builds from HCI 18.X, this key replaces PSKEY_UART_SEQ_WINSIZE.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_UART_HOST_WAKE 0x01c7 uint16[4] 4, 500, 10, 0

UART host wakeup

This PSKey configures the use of a wakeup signal by the BlueCore to wake the peer UART device from a low power state. The wakeup signal, which may be either a UART break condition or a pulse on a PIO line, is specified by PSKEY_UART_HOST_WAKE_SIGNAL.

If this PSKey's mechanism is turned on, the firmware judges when the peer may have entered its deep sleep state based on timers, and the local device can be set to emit a wakeup signal before sending data to the peer. Normally the length of the break condition is set to be sufficient to allow the peer to come fully awake as the local device normally sends a message to the peer afterwards.

Most systems do not require the BlueCore to emit a wakeup signal to wake up the peer device. Systems using the BCSP transport, for example, support the host and baseband entering a deep sleep state, in which their UARTs are disabled. The devices may enter deep sleep when they choose, without warning that they are about to enter deep sleep and without signalling when they are in deep sleep. When one device wishes to send data to its peer it sends a message; the message can be lost (because the peer's UART may be turned off) but the presence of the message rouses the peer. For reliable BCSP channels the message is resent if it has not been acknowledged after a delay (set by PSKEY_UART_ACK_TIMEOUT), and the message normally gets through the second time, as the peer is then awake. This mechanism is adequate for most systems, but using a host wakeup signal may reduce delay implied by PSKEY_UART_ACK_TIMEOUT.

This use of wakeup signals by the BlueCore is turned off by default, as this suits most systems.

This PSKey has four uint16 parameters:

    Enable: Values: 1 => enable mechanism
                    4 => disable mechanism
    Sleep_Delay: Milliseconds after tx to host or rx from host, after
                    which host is assumed to have gone into its
                    deep sleep state. (Range 1 -> 65535.)
                    When using BCSP or H5 host transports it is
                    recommended that this is greater than the
                    acknowledge delay (set by PSKEY_UART_ACK_TIMEOUT).
    Break_Length: Duration of wake signal in milliseconds.
                    (Range 1 -> 1000.)
    Pause_Length: Milliseconds between end of wake signal and
                    sending data to the host. (Range 0 -> 1000.)

In builds from HCI 18.X, this key replaces PSKEY_UART_HOST_INITIAL_STATE, PSKEY_UART_HOST_ATTENTION_SPAN, PSKEY_UART_HOST_WAKEUP_TIME, and PSKEY_UART_HOST_WAKEUP_WAIT.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_HOSTIO_THROTTLE_TIMEOUT 0x01c8 TIME 200 * MILLISECOND

Host interface performance control.

This PSKey modifies the behaviour of the BlueCore's host interface code. Only configure this PSKey on specific advice from CSR.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_UART_HOST_WAKE_SIGNAL 0x01ca uint16 0x0000

Signal to use for uart host wakeup protocol

BlueCore can be configured to output a wakeup signal to the host prior to sending it data if it considers that the host may be in a low power state. PSKEY_UART_HOST_WAKE enables this wakeup signalling and specifies the various timers required. This PSKey specifies the wakeup signal to use: a UART break signal, a pulse on a PIO line or, for the H4DS transport only, a repeated byte sequence.

This PSKey's value is split into two:
  Bits [3:0] hold a value that specifies the Host Wake Mechanism.
  Valid values are:
                     0 - repeated byte sequence (only for H4DS)
                     1 - positive pulse on PIO
                     2 - negative pulse on PIO
                     3 - UART BREAK condition

  Bits [7:4] hold a value that specifies the PIO pin to be used if a
  PIO pulse was specified as the Host Wake Mechanism.

If the Host Wake Mechanism is 0x00, BlueCore sends a repeated byte sequence. The duration of the byte train is specified by PSKEY_H4DS_WAKE_DURATION. This mechanism is available for the H4DS transport only. The byte sequence has been chosen to work well with BlueCore's Baud rate detection capability.

If 0x00 is chosen when the host transport is not H4DS a UART BREAK condition is used.

If the Host Wake Mechanism is 0x01 then a positive pulse is signalled on the PIO pin selected by Bits [7:4]. (Value 0x0 in Bits [7:4] selects PIO[0], value 0x01 selects PIO[1], etc.). The duration of the pulse is specified by PSKEY_H4DS_WAKE_DURATION for the H4DS transport and by PSKEY_UART_HOST_WAKE for all other host transports.

If the Host Wake Mechanism is 0x02 then a negative pulse is signalled on the PIO pin selected by Bits [7:4]. The duration of the pulse is specified by PSKEY_H4DS_WAKE_DURATION for the H4DS transport, and by PSKEY_UART_HOST_WAKE for all other host transports.

If the Host Wake Mechanism is 0x03 then a break condition is signalled by the UART. The duration of the break signal is specified by PSKEY_H4DS_WAKE_DURATION for the H4DS transport, and by PSKEY_UART_HOST_WAKE for all other host transports.

For more information see CSR document "Host Wakeup Application Note", CS-101406-An, on the CSR support website.

This PSKey defines how many bits the Digital Audio Interface clocks per sample. For I2S, if the number of bits per sample is larger than the internal audio format used by BlueCore, the additional bits are output as zeros in the LSBs.

This PS Key value is used to calculate the port clock rate and so is ignored if PSKEY_DIGITAL_AUDIO_RATE is used to define a specific rate.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_BCSP_PULL_CONTROL 0x01df uint16 0x0000

Bus-keeper/pull-disable for BCSP/H5 host transports

This PSKey configures the enhanced pull device control features present on some BlueCore chips for input lines associated with the BCSP and H5 host transports (i.e., the UART lines).

The bits in this PSKey only come into effect if BCSP or H5 is selected as the host transport at boot time. The selected modes are enabled at boot time during BCSP/H5 initialisation and never disabled.

Bit 0 controls "bus-keeper" mode. When an input is in "bus-keeper" mode, the polarity of the internal pull device follows that of the last externally driven input. (This mode has no effect on pins that are driven as outputs by the BlueCore.) If this bit is clear (the default), "bus-keeper" mode is never enabled; if set, "bus-keeper" mode is enabled at the appropriate time by the firmware.

Bit 1 controls "pull-disable" mode. Normally, all inputs have a pull device with defined polarity (pull-up or pull-down); in "pull-disable" mode, the pull device is disabled entirely, leaving a true tri-state input. If this bit is clear (the default), the pull device is never disabled; if set, the pull device is disabled at the appropriate time by the firmware.

Note: In general, if "pull-disable" mode is enabled, the "bus-keeper" bit has no effect.

Note: Incorrect configuration of this key can lead to excessive power consumption and can potentially damage the chip. If a pull device is disabled, but the input is not driven externally (which includes not being physically connected, or even not being brought out on the chip package), that input floats, leading to excessive current flow.

The default value of this PSKey is safe in this regard. "Bus-keeper" mode has no such concerns.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_H4DS_PULL_CONTROL 0x01e0 uint16 0x0000

Bus-keeper/pull-disable for H4DS host transport

This PSKey configures the enhanced pull device control features present on some BlueCore chips for input lines associated with the H4DS host transport (i.e., the UART lines). See PSKEY_BCSP_PULL_CONTROL for more information on the pull device control features.

The bits in this PSKey only come into effect if H4DS is selected as the host transport at boot time. The selected modes are enabled at boot time during H4DS initialisation and never disabled.

Bit 0 controls "bus-keeper" mode: if this bit is clear (the default), "bus-keeper" mode is never enabled; if set, "bus-keeper" mode is enabled at the appropriate time by the firmware.

Bit 1 controls "pull-disable" mode: if this bit is clear (the default), the pull device is never disabled; if set, the pull device is disabled at the appropriate time by the firmware.

Note: Incorrect configuration of this PSKey can lead to excessive power consumption and can potentially damage the chip. The default value is safe in this regard.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_PCM_PULL_CONTROL 0x01e2 uint16 0x0011

Bus-keeper/pull-disable for PCM bus(es)

This PSKey configures the enhanced pull device control features present on some BlueCore chips for input lines associated with the PCM/I2S interface(s). See PSKEY_BCSP_PULL_CONTROL for more information on the pull device control features.

The affected lines on each interface are PCM_IN, PCM_OUT, PCM_CLK, and PCM_SYNC. Because these can only be controlled as a group, any unused lines must be connected and driven appropriately if the pull control features are to be used.

There are two complementary bits used to control each feature for each PCM interface. One controls the configuration while the interface is actively being used to transfer data, and another controls the configuration while it is inactive.

The following bits in this PSKey take effect when a PCM interface is actively being used by the BlueCore to transfer data:

Bit 0 controls "bus-keeper" mode on the first PCM bus: if this bit is clear, "bus-keeper" mode is not enabled during transfers; if set (the default), "bus-keeper" mode is enabled during transfers.

Bit 1 controls "pull-disable" mode on the first PCM bus: if this bit is clear (the default), the pull device is not disabled during transfers; if set, the pull device is disabled during transfers.

The following bits in this key take effect when a PCM interface is inactive, and not being used by the BlueCore to transfer data:

Bit 2 controls "bus-keeper" mode on the first PCM bus: if this bit is clear (the default), "bus-keeper" mode is not enabled whilst the interface is inactive; if set, "bus-keeper" mode is enabled whilst the interface is inactive.

Bit 3 controls "pull-disable" mode on the first PCM bus: if this bit is clear (the default), the pull device is not disabled whilst the interface is inactive; if set, the pull device is disabled whilst the interface is inactive.

Bits [7:4] similarly control the second PCM bus, where present.

For Unified-25 firmware and later, the following bits in this key take effect when a PCM interface is in the intermediate state:

Bit 8 controls "bus-keeper-disable" mode on the first PCM bus: if this bit is clear (the default), "bus-keeper" mode is enabled when the bus is in the intermediate state; if set, "bus-keeper" mode is disabled when the bus is in the intermediate state.

Bit 9 controls "pull-disable" mode on the first PCM bus: if this bit is clear (the default), the pull device is not disabled when the bus is in the intermediate state; if set, the pull device is disabled when the bus is in the intermediate state.

Bits [13:12] similarly control the second PCM bus, where present.

NOTE: Incorrect configuration of this key can lead to excessive power consumption and can potentially damage the chip. The default value is safe in this regard.

PSKEY_UART_BITRATE 0x01ea uint32 38400

This PSKey replaces PSKEY_UART_BAUDRATE for BlueCore7+ chips.

Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_USB_HOST_WAKE_ENABLE 0x01eb uint16 0x0004

Enable USB host wakeup

This PSKey enables the host wakeup mechanism for USB. If the USB host wakeup mechanism is turned on, the firmware judges when the peer may have entered its deep sleep state based on timers, and the local device can be set to emit a wakeup signal before sending data to the peer. Normally, the length of the host wake signal is set to be sufficient to allow the peer to come fully awake because the local device normally sends a message to the peer straight afterwards.

This PSKey also enables another setting, Tx_Remains_Asleep. If this setting is enabled the chip assumes that the host remains asleep even when it has transmitted data. This means the chip attempts to wake the host whenever it has data to transmit, regardless of whether the host transmitted recently or not. The only time it does not wake the host for a transmit is if it is transmitting for a second time within the host wake period, and so woke the host recently.

This PSKey's value is a bitfield:
        Bits [3:0]: Enable: 1: enable mechanism
                                  4: disable mechanism
        Bit 4: Tx_Remains_Asleep: 1: enabled
                                  0: disabled

BlueCore use of wakeup signals is disabled by default because this suits most systems.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_USB_HOST_WAKE_TIME 0x01ec uint32[] 500000, 500, 0

USB host wakeup times

This PSKey configures BlueCore use of a wakeup signal to wake the peer USB device from a low power state. This wakeup mechanism is enabled via PSKEY_USB_HOST_WAKE_ENABLE. The wakeup signal, which is a pulse on a PIO line, is specified via a separate PSKey, PSKEY_USB_HOST_WAKE_SIGNAL.

This PS key has three uint32 parameters:
   Sleep_Delay: Microseconds after tx to host, or rx from
                        host after which the host is assumed
                        to have gone into its deep sleep state.
                        (Range 1 -> 4294967295)
   HWake_Signal_Length: Minimum duration of wake signal in
                        microseconds.
                        (Range 0 -> 1000000)
   Pause_Length: Microseconds between end of wake signal
                        and sending of data to the host.
                        (Range 0 -> 1000000)

The minimum HWake_Signal_Length that can actually be produced is 15us achieved by setting the value to 0us.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_USB_HOST_WAKE_SIGNAL 0x01ed uint16 0x0031

Signal to use for the USB host wakeup protocol

If the host wakeup mechanism for USB is enabled via PSKEY_USB_HOST_WAKE_ENABLE, this PSKey can specify the wakeup signal to use: either a positive or negative pulse on a PIO line.

This PSKey's value is a bitfield:
        Bits [3:0]: Host Wake Mechanism. 1 => positive pulse on PIO
                                         2 => negative pulse on PIO
        Bits [7:4]: PIO pin selection. Value selects PIO pin.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_USB_DATA_PLUS_PULL_CONTROL 0x01f0 uint16 AS_SOON_AS_POSSIBLE

Signal to determine when D+ is activated on boot

By default, D+ pullup is activated during initialization as per the USB standard. If PSKEY_USB_DATA_PLUS_PULL_CONTROL is set to AFTER_CONFIGURATION ('sets D+ when configuration is done'), D+ pullup is only activated when configuration is complete. If PSKEY_USB_CHARGER_DETECTION_ENABLE is set to 'Voltage source detection' then the value of PSKEY_USB_DATA_PLUS_PULL_CONTROL is ignored and the firmware always acts as if PSKEY_USB_DATA_PLUS_PULL_CONTROL has been set to AFTER_CONFIGURATION ('sets D+ when configuration is done').

Allowed Values
AS_SOON_AS_POSSIBLE 0 sets D+ at boot (<100ms)
AFTER_CONFIGURATION 1 sets D+ when configuration is done (when ready)

Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_AUDIO_DECOUPLE_CAP 0x01f4 uint8 Default 0x3
Minimum 0
Maximum 0x3

audio decouple capacitor

This PSKey specifies an override to the default audio decoupling setting. This PSKey is read at audio initialisation and set if present.

For HAVE_GORDON_AUDIO these values are assigned from the enumeration: 0: decoupling off (bad audio) 1: 0.5V reference (best for DAC) 2: 0.7V reference (best for ADC) 3: 0.95V reference (best for mic bias)


Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_WD_TIMEOUT 0x01f7 TIME Default 5 * SECOND
Minimum 0
Maximum 60 * SECOND

Watchdog timeout (microseconds)

BlueCore has hardware support to run a watchdog timer. This is a timer that is set to the value of this PSKey every time it is "kicked" (written to by the firmware). If the firmware fails to kick the watchdog within this period the chip's watchdog hardware forces a hardware reset of the chip. This supports the possibility that the chip's firmware might crash or hang up.

The value is in microseconds. If the value is zero the watchdog is disabled.

This PSKey is used in conjunction with PSKEY_ENABLE_SOFT_WD to enable the watchdog in its debug mode. See description of PSKEY_ENABLE_SOFT_WD.

Also see the description of PSKEY_WD_PERIOD.

Type TIME is fundamentally a uint32. Value SECOND is 1000000.


Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_WD_PERIOD 0x01f8 TIME Default 3 * SECOND
Minimum 100 * MILLISECOND
Maximum 60 * SECOND

Watchdog period (microseconds)

This PSKey sets the watchdog period, (nominally) the microseconds between kicking the watchdog hardware.

This should be no more than 70% of PSKEY_WD_TIMEOUT (unless the timeout value is zero).

Type TIME is fundamentally a uint32. Value SECOND is 1000000.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_HOST_INTERFACE 0x01f9 phys_bus phys_bus_bcsp

Host interface

This PSKey selects the physical connection that is used to pass information to and from the host - BCSP, H4, USB, etc. Only one of these can be used at a time, mainly because the USB interface uses some of the same chip pins as the UART.

Much of the chip's support for BCSP/H5 is performed by hardware. This allows interrupt routines to deal with complete BCSP/H5 packets. When the chip uses its UART in a more naive fashion, e.g., for H4, this support must be disabled. The UART's hardware support for BCSP/H5 must be enabled via PSKEY_UART_CONFIG_BCSP/H5.

The H4 specification requires the use of UART hardware flow control and no use of parity. These must also be set via PSKEY_UART_CONFIG_H4.

Type phys_bus is really a uint16. The PSKey takes values:

        0: No chip to host connection
        1: BCSP
        2: H2 - USB
        3: H4 - UART
        4: VM access to the UART
        6: H5
        7: H4DS
        9: SDIO
       10: TBus

Note: The "H5" host transport protocol is properly known as the "Three-Wire UART Transport Layer", but is commonly known as H5 within CSR.

Allowed Values
phys_bus_none 0 No host to chip connection
phys_bus_bcsp 1 UART link running BCSP
phys_bus_usb 2 USB link
phys_bus_h4 3 UART link running H4
phys_bus_usr 4 VM access to the UART
phys_bus_h5 6 UART link running H5
phys_bus_h4ds 7 UART link running H4 with deep sleep
phys_bus_sdio 9 SDIO or CSPI link
phys_bus_tbus 10 Hostio over Transaction Bus

Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_HQ_HOST_TIMEOUT 0x01fb TIME Default 5 * SECOND
Minimum 1 * SECOND
Maximum 60 * SECOND

HQ host command timeout

Each HQ (host query) message sent to the host should provoke a corresponding reply from the host. This PSKey sets the period in microseconds for which the HQ task waits before giving up waiting for the reply.

Type TIME is fundamentally a uint32. Value SECOND is 1000000.

See PSKEY_HQ_ACTIVE.

For more information see the CSR documents "HQ Protocol", CS-102660-SP and "BlueCore HQ Commands", CS-101607-SP.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_HQ_ACTIVE 0x01fc bool TRUE

Enable Host Query Task

The device's HQ (host query) task can send messages to the host over either BCSP channel 3 or tunnelled through the CSR manufacturer-specific HCI extensions. The channel's protocol has an RPC-style structure. This means each message should cause the host to send a corresponding response back to the chip. The protocol is described in document "HQ Protocol", CS-102660-SP, available from the CSR support website.

If PSKEY_HQ_ACTIVE is set to TRUE (1), then the device's HQ task is enabled. If PSKEY_HQ_ACTIVE is set to FALSE (0), then the device's HQ task is configured so that no HQ traffic is sent to the host.

See PSKEY_HQ_HOST_TIMEOUT.

For more information see the CSR documents "HQ Protocol", CS-102660-SP and "BlueCore HQ Commands", CS-101607-SP.

Type bool is fundamentally a uint16 with values 0 and 1 mapping to FALSE and TRUE.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_BCCMD_SECURITY_ACTIVE 0x01fd bool FALSE

Enable configuration security

The firmware's bccmd task presents a command interpreter to the host in a manner similar to HCI. The command interpreter's command set is not part of any Bluetooth standard. It is specific to the BlueCore chips and firmware. The command set is used for monitoring and controlling the chip, running radio tests, etc. The command set is described in document "BCCMD Commands," CS-101482-SP.

The command interpreter is accessed via the BCCMD protocol. The BCCMD protocol is described in document "BCCMD Protocol", CS-101676-SP. This can run over a BCSP channel (channel 2, see document "BCSP Channel Allocation", CS-101680-SP), over a CSR manufacturer-specific HCI extension channel or over the chip's SPI interface.

The bccmd task provides a simple access control mechanism for BCCMD commands presented over BCSP or HCI-extension; this mechanism is not present for SPI access.

This PSKey enables the security mechanism. The security mechanism is described in the document "BCCMD Protocol Security", CS-101679-SP.

When a BlueCore module is freshly manufactured this bool flag is set FALSE. The host may then read and write all PS values and can run all of the BCCMD commands. This allows the manufacturer to configure the Bluetooth module.

When the configuration is complete the manufacturer sets this PSKey to TRUE. This enables the PS and BCCMD access controls. When set TRUE this PSKey cannot be set back to FALSE via BCSP running over the BCSP extension channel or the HCI extension channel. Setting security active is therefore normally a one-way operation.

Type bool is fundamentally a uint16 with values 0 and 1 mapping to FALSE and TRUE.

For more information see "BCCMD Protocol Security", CS-101679-SP, "BCCMD Protocol", CS-101676-SP, "BCCMD Commands," CS-101482-SP and "BCSP Channel Allocation", CS-101680-SP.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_ANA_FREQ 0x01fe uint16 26000

Crystal frequency

This PSKey configures the BlueCore hardware to work with a particular reference clock frequency.

For chips prior to BlueCore2-ROM the default, 4, configures the chip to use a 16 MHz reference. The value defines a reference frequency of n*250 kHz where n is an integer, but there is a pseudo-random mapping from n to the required value. This is described in supporting documentation.

For BlueCore2-ROM and subsequent chips, the value defines the reference frequency in units of 1 kHz. The default value, 26000, configures the chip to use a 26 MHz reference. If the PSKey is absent or the value is zero, the chip attempts to pick a frequency; this cannot be relied on to be the correct frequency, so the radio is not usable.

The automatic clock frequency detection mechanism is likely to be most useful in ROM parts, and is described in document "Booting BlueCore ROM", CS-101436-ME, available from the CSR support website.

When an external crystal is in use, it is usually necessary to make fine adjustments to allow for variations in individual crystals. See the description of PSKEY_ANA_FTRIM and PSKEY_ANA_FTRIM_OFFSET for details.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_PIO_PROTECT_MASK 0x0202 uint16 0

Access to PIO0 - PIO15 pins

Each BlueCore chip contains a PIO port that may, under BCCMD or VM control, be used as a general I/O port. However, various optional hardware and software configurations require the use of certain PIO pins for their own needs. For example, an optional external PA/LNA block may be driven using PIO pins 0 and 1.

This PSKey prevents applications from changing PIO pins that are required for lower level functions. This blocking action applies to host-based applications requesting PIO changes via BCCMD and to VM applications running on the chip.

Some of the lower level functions automatically prevent the application from changing the state of PIOs being used by the function by overriding the value of the relevant bits in this PSKey. This includes the PIOs related to PSKEY_TXRX_PIO_CONTROL, PSKEY_USB_PIO_VBUS, PSKEY_USB_PIO_DETACH, PSKEY_USB_PIO_PULLUP, PSKEY_USB_PIO_WAKEUP and PSKEY_USB_PIO_RESUME. So, for example if PSKEY_USB_PIO_DETACH claims the use of PIO[5] then this PIO cannot be changed by application code no matter what the value of PSKEY_PIO_PROTECT_MASK is.

Bits [7:0] of this uint16 PSKey map to PIO0 to PIO7 respectively. If a bit of the PSKey's value is set high then application code cannot change the value of the corresponding PIO port pin.

Note: On the current Casira motherboard, PIO2 is connected to USB+ via a 1k5 resistor. The USB+ pin doubles as the UART RTS line on BlueCore, so care must be taken if an application uses PIO2.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_STUB 0x0207 uint16 0

Stub

A key that can be harmlessly read or written.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_TXRX_PIO_CONTROL 0x0209 uint16 0

TX and RX PIO control

The chip contains a radio power amplifier (PA) and low noise amplifier (LNA), allowing it to act as a limited-range Bluetooth device. Although this is adequate for many applications, some systems require more range and so use external PA/LNA devices.

If external devices are used, two pins of the PIO port are allocated to control them. On BlueCore7 onwards, the pins used are configurable by PSKEY_TXRX_PIO_TX and PSKEY_TXRX_PIO_RX. On earlier chips the LNA is enabled by pin PIO0 and the PA by pin PIO1.

Before transmitting, the chip normally ramps up the power to the internal PA, then it ramps it down again afterwards. However, if a suitable external PA is used it may be possible to ramp the power externally using the AUX_DAC pin.

This PSKey sets the PA/LNA configuration:

    0: The two PIO lines are not driven for Tx and Rx. The chip's
        internal PA/LNA is used.

    1: The two PIO lines are driven high to enable the external PA
        and LNA. Tx power ramping is controlled by the internal PA.

    2: The two PIO lines are driven high to enable the external PA
        and LNA. Tx power ramping is controlled on the external PA
        via the chip's AUX_DAC pin. The
        "external_pa" entries in PSKEY_POWER_TABLE are used.

    3: The two PIO lines are driven low to enable the external PA
        and LNA. Tx power ramping is controlled by the internal PA.

    4: PIO lines driven high for external PA and LNA;
        Tx power ramping controlled by internal PA. External PA
        controlled (not ramped) by chip's AUX_DAC pin. The
        "external_pa" entries in PSKEY_POWER_TABLE are used.

    5: PIO lines driven high for external PA and LNA;
        Tx power ramping controlled by internal PA. External LNA
        gain controlled by chip's AUX_DAC pin. The AUX_DAC
        is varied by the AGC between zero and its maximum in 16 steps.

Hardware restrictions prevent the use of active low PIO pins and external PA ramping.

The behaviour of the chip's AUX_DAC pin is undefined unless this key is set to 2 or 4.

See also:
        PSKEY_LC_MAX_TX_POWER
        PSKEY_TX_GAIN_RAMP
        PSKEY_LC_POWER_TABLE
        PSKEY_LC_DEFAULT_TX_POWER
        PSKEY_TXRX_PIO_TX
        PSKEY_TXRX_PIO_RX.

Allowed Values
0 PIO does not drive tx+rx, internal amp ramps power
1 PIO drives tx+rx, internal amp ramps power
2 PIO drives tx+rx, aux dac ramps external amp gain
3 PIO drives tx+rx inverted, internal amp ramps power
4 PIO drives tx+rx, internal amp ramps power, aux dac sets external amp gain
5 PIO drives tx+rx, internal amp ramps power, aux dac sets external LNA

Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_ANA_RX_LEVEL 0x020b uint16 Default 3
Minimum 0
Maximum 16

ANA_RX_LVL register initial value

This PSKey sets the initial value of the chip's $ANA_RX_LVL register.

Do not alter the value of this PSKey except with specific advice from CSR.


Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_PCM0_ATTENUATION 0x020f uint16 Default 3
Minimum 0
Maximum 7

Volume control on PCM channels

Some Motorola codecs allow their gain to be controlled by 3 extra bits received at the end of a 13 bit PCM sample.

This PSKey sets the value of these three bits for SCO data sent from chip's PCM channels (channels 0-3 on PCM1 and PCM2, if exists). It is expected that low values will map to high volume levels, though the firmware has no knowledge of this: it just passes the bits into the PCM stream. If this value is not needed then it may make sense to set this key to zero.

It is possible that the firmware will acquire dynamically-settable attenuation controls for the PCM channel(s). In this case this PSKey will set the initial attenuation value.


Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_IQ_TRIM_CHANNEL 0x0214 uint16 Default 44
Minimum 0
Maximum 78

IQ calibration channel

This PSKey sets the Bluetooth radio channel on which to perform radio trim auto calibration. This can be in the range 0..78.


Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_TX_OFFSET_HALF_MHZ 0x0217 int16 Default 1
Minimum -16
Maximum 15

Transmit offset

This PSKeys sets the frequency offset used for transmit, in units of 500 kHz.

For BlueCore5+ it controls only the basic rate Class 2 transmit offset.

If PSKEY_ENABLE_TX_IF_REDUCTION is present, transmit IFs configured to be +/- 500 kHz may optionally be slightly reduced. Please see that key for a description.

Do not alter the value of this PSKey except with specific advice from CSR.


Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_UART_SLEEP_TIMEOUT 0x0222 uint16 Default 1000
Minimum 0
Maximum 30 * 1000

Time in ms to deep sleep if nothing received

This PSKey applies when the host interface is BCSP, H5, H4DS or VM access to the UART, and depends on the key PSKEY_DEEP_SLEEP_STATE being set to allow deep sleep. If there has been no transmission from the host for at least this number of milliseconds, and there is no data to send, then the chip may go into deep sleep, depending on restrictions from any other source. Set the value to 0 to inhibit deep sleep for BCSP, H5, H4DS or VM UART access, but it has no effect if another host interface is in use.

If using BCSP or H5, do not set this sleep timeout to a non-zero value that is less than or equal to either of the BlueCore's retransmit period (configured in PSKEY_UART_ACK_TIMEOUT) or the peer device's retransmit period.

Note: The "H5" host transport protocol is properly known as the "Three-Wire UART Transport Layer", but is commonly known as H5 within CSR.

Any data on the UART wakes the chip from deep sleep. However the particular transmission that wakes it is lost. The chip wakes up about 5ms later.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_DEEP_SLEEP_STATE 0x0229 deep_sleep_state DEEP_SLEEP_ALWAYS_ACCURATE

Deep sleep state usage

BlueCore has two types of low power state. "Deep sleep" allows most saving, and so has more constraints on its use. This PSKey configures deep sleep.

Type deep_sleep_state can be treated as a uint16, taking these values:

    NEVER (0): Deep sleep is never be used.
    ALWAYS (1): Deep sleep is used whenever possible.
    INACTIVE (2): Deep sleep when there are no ACL
                         connections.
    ALWAYS_ACCURATE (3): Deep sleep is used whenever possible;
                         the firmware assumes the module has an
                         accurate slow clock which does not
                         need calibrating after startup.

The ALWAYS_ACCURATE setting should be used when the slow clock source is stable enough to not require periodic re-calibrating.

This setting saves power because the firmware does not need to calibrate the slow clock against the standard 20 ppm clock after the frequency of the slow clock has been determined at boot.

Crystal-controlled slow clock sources should not require periodic re-calibration whereas use of the BlueCore's internal low power slow speed clock requires periodic recalibration.

From BlueCore7 some devices support the internal derivation of a slow clock from the fast accurate clock. If this option is used the fast clock continues to run (in a low power mode if used a quartz crystal) to support this function even when the device is in deep sleep.

In this case the ALWAYS_ACCURATE option should be selected because slow clock frequency is stable.

If the BlueCore in use does not support deep sleep timing derived from the fast clock then ALWAYS_ACCURATE should only be used when PSKEY_DEEP_SLEEP_USE_EXTERNAL_CLOCK is set to TRUE and a suitably stable external slow clock source is available.

Deep sleep may be entered when an ACL connection is in hold or sniff; hence accuracy may be lost when using the internal low power slow speed clock. In certain situations, where power saving is not a major priority but maintaining accuracy of the clock is (for example, a network access point), it may be advantageous to disable deep sleep mode with this key.

Note that changing this PSKEY has implications for the setting of PSKEY_DEVICE_DRIFT. See the description of that key for details.

Deep sleep also causes slightly slower response on the UART when BCSP is in use if no data has been received for a while. See PSKEY_UART_SLEEP_TIMEOUT.

This does not affect the other low power states, in which clock accuracy is not lost.

Allowed Values
DEEP_SLEEP_NEVER 0 deep sleep will not be used
DEEP_SLEEP_ALWAYS 1 deep sleep used whenever possible
DEEP_SLEEP_INACTIVE 2 deep sleep may be used if no links
DEEP_SLEEP_ALWAYS_ACCURATE 3 deep sleep whenever possible and assume slow clock is accurate

Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_HCI_HANDLE_FREEZE_PERIOD 0x0237 TIME 15 * SECOND

Time for which HCI handle is frozen after link removal

This PSKey holds the default period in microseconds for which data reception on a HCI connection handle is maintained after the corresponding connection has been removed.

Reception must be enabled for this additional period as stray late data may come from the host. The freeze period should therefore be sufficiently large for the host to realise that a HCI connection has been removed or has failed.

Any data received during the period when the connection handle is frozen is diverted into a dummy buffer and so effectively discarded.

Any data received after this period may result in either a chip panic PANIC_HOSTIO_MISPLACED_DATA (when the transport is BCSP, H5, SDIO or USB) or a fault FAULT_H4_RX_BAD_PDU for most H4-based transports. Alternatively when the transport is BCSP or H5 a PANIC_HOSTIO_DATA_IN_BUFFER_ERROR may be seen and when the transport is USB a PANIC_USB_HW_FATAL_ERROR may be seen. On firmware builds from the 24 branch onwards, some H4 transports may PANIC_HOSTIO_MISPLACED_DATA or PANIC_HOSTIO_DATA_IN_BUFFER_ERROR rather than FAULT_H4_RX_BAD_PDU.

The value stored by this PSKey is also the minimum time before an HCI connection handle can be re-allocated for a new connection.

Maintaining a connection handle for this additional period consumes some of the chip's resources. Therefore creating and destroying connections rapidly relative to the freeze period results in a resource leak. After the number of currently frozen handles reaches a limit set by PSKEY_MAX_FROZEN_HCI_HANDLES, further attempts to create connections are rejected.

Type TIME is fundamentally a uint32. Value SECOND is 1000000.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_MAX_FROZEN_HCI_HANDLES 0x0238 uint16 20

Maximum number of frozen HCI handles

This PSKey holds the default number of frozen connection handles at which further connection requests are refused.

After a connection has been removed, its HCI handle is maintained active for a short period, defined by PSKEY_HCI_HANDLE_FREEZE_PERIOD. Some resources are required to maintain the link active and so if connections are created and destroyed rapidly in relation to this period, resources are gradually consumed.

To prevent constraining the operation of any existing connections due to lack of memory, further connection requests are rejected when the number of currently frozen handles reaches the value stored under this PSKey.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_PAGETABLE_DESTRUCTION_DELAY 0x0239 TIME 50*MILLISECOND

Delay from freezing buf handle to deleting page table

This PSKey sets the default delay in microseconds from the point at which a buffer is redirected until its page table and any MMU memory allocated to it can be freed.

Buffers used to receive data from the host are redirected to point to a dummy buffer when a connection is torn down. This enables reception to continue on this buffer (connection) handle for a certain period after a link is removed.

Most of the buffer resources can be freed as soon as the handle is redirected. The buffer page table address however is cached by the CSR chip hardware during the reception of an HCI data packet payload. The page table therefore cannot be destroyed for a period equal to the duration of the largest packet that the host can send.

Type TIME is fundamentally a uint32. Value SECOND is 1000000.


Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_IQ_TRIM_PIO_SETTINGS 0x023a uint8 Default 6
Minimum 0
Maximum 15

IQ PIO settings

This PSKEY defines the state of external TX & RX amp enable PIOs (defined in PSKEY_TXRX_PIO_TX & PSKEY_TXRX_PIO_RX) during automatic IQ calibration. This PSKEY is valid for pre-BlueCore 5 (which uses lower 4 bits of uint8) & BlueCore 7 chips (which uses lower 3 bits of uint8).

For pre-BlueCore 5 & BlueCore 7 chips if Bit 2 is set to 1 it enables TX & RX amp enable PIOs to be set to a particular state during IQ trim. In this case, the state of TX & RX amp enable PIOs is set by the PSKey's bits 1 and 0 respectively. If Bit 2 is set to 0 then the existing values of the PIO lines will be preserved through the IQ trim and bits 0 and 1 of the PSKey are ignored. For pre-BlueCore 5 If PSKey Bit 3 is set to 1 then the external transmit power control DAC is enabled at its maximum setting during IQ trim.

During the auto-IQ trim both transmitter and receiver are active. Energy from the transmitter is looped back to the receiver which is used to measure the level of image rejection which has been achieved. For this to work successfully the transmitter must be presented with a respectable load.

For Class 1 modules the transmitter drives a PA. The impedance presented to the transmitter is generally respectable even if the PA is not switched on during the auto-IQ trim.

For modules with no PA the transmitter output is coupled via a balun to the transmit/receive switch. The impedance presented to the transmitter during auto-IQ trim is dependent on the setting of the transmit/receive switch, which is governed by external TX & RX amp enable PIOs. However different switch models exhibit different behaviour with the PIO control lines, even switch models from the same manufacturer. For example, it is possible for the switch to present a high impedance, ground or even a time varying impedance to the transmitter.

For modules with a PA, external TX & RX amp enable PIOs should be 0 to ensure that the PA is disabled during auto-IQ trim (although certain modules invert these PIO lines, requiring different settings).

For modules with no PA the PSKey should be set to place the transmit/receive switch in the state that provides optimum performance for the auto-IQ trim algorithm.


Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_DEEP_SLEEP_WAKE_CTS 0x023c uint16 Default 0
Maximum 2

Exit deep sleep on CTS line activity

Deep sleep is allowed with some (but not all) host interfaces that use the UART. This key determines whether the chip will wake from deep sleep due to activity on the CTS line from the host, and also due to activity on the data RX line. Three values are allowed.

    0: The chip wakes due to activity on the data RX line,
       but does not wake due to activity on the CTS line. This is
       the default.
    1: The chip wakes due to activity on either the data RX line
       or the CTS line.
    2: The chip wakes due to activity on the CTS line, but does
       not wake due to activity on the data RX line.

Note that the chip is sensitive to the level on both lines: if the line is held low, and wake-up on the line has been enabled, the chip will be kept out of deep sleep. Note also that the chip is sensitive to the lines themselves; it is not actually required that there is a host using the UART for data communication.

If the host interface is set to `none', i.e. the firmware has been informed that no host communication is in use, it is still possible to use the CTS line to wake the chip. However the data RX line is ignored. This is because this line is floating in many hardware configurations with no host interface.

The key is ignored if the host interface is USB.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_FC_HC2H_FLUSH_DELAY 0x023d TIME 10 * SECOND

Delay from disconnect to flushing HC->H FC tokens

The default delay in microseconds from destroying a connection until any outstanding host controller to host flow control tokens are flushed.

This delay is required to workaround a race hazard in the hci specification. The host might not acknowledge packets sent around the time when it is sent a disconnect event - the buffers used for these packets should thus be assumed to be free by the host controller. However as the processing of the disconnect is not synchronised on the host and host controller, a delay is required to ensure the host has actually flushed its buffers and thus prevent temporary overruns.

The time delay from disconnection to flushing the buffers should be less than the time for which a connection handle is frozen after disconnection (defined by PSKEY_HCI_HANDLE_FREEZE_PERIOD). This ensures the handle is not re-allocated during the flush delay and thus that the buffers for the new link are not interfered with.

(Type TIME is fundamentally a uint32. Value SECOND is 1000000.)


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_RX_HIGHSIDE 0x023e bool FALSE

Disable the HIGHSIDE bit in ANA_CONFIG

If this key is FALSE, the local oscillator frequency is 1.5 MHz less than the carrier frequency to be received, whereas if it is TRUE the LO frequency is 1.5 MHz higher than the carrier frequency.

For chips starting with BlueCore2-ROM and versions of firmware starting with 17.4, this is taken as an input to the algorithm which calculates the RF frequency parameters for each receive channel. The result may be that some channels do not use the value of this key.

(Type bool is fundamentally a uint16 with values 0 and 1 mapping to FALSE and TRUE.)


Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_XTAL_LVL 0x0241 uint8 Default 5
Minimum 0
Maximum 15

Crystal bias level

Sets the bias level to the crystal. Low values may not work. High values may give worse phase noise.


Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_TX_FILTER_CONFIG 0x0243 uint32 Default 0x77070003
Minimum 0
Maximum 0xFFFFFFFF

TX filter configuration

Configures the transmit filter for optimum modulation. For CSR use only.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_CLOCK_REQUEST_ENABLE 0x0246 uint16 0

External clock request enable

The BlueCore can be configured to use a PIO to indicate that it requires an external high-speed clock reference at the frequency configured by PSKEY_ANA_FREQ. This line will be inactive when no clock reference is required (for instance, when the BlueCore is in deep sleep).

If set to 0, no PIO is used as a clock request.

If set to 1, PIO[6] is active when an external clock reference is required, and is inactive otherwise.

If set to 2, PIO[2] is active when an external clock reference is required, and is inactive otherwise.

If set to 3, PIO[2] is active when an external clock reference is required or if PIO[3] is high, and is inactive when a clock reference is not required and PIO[3] is low.

Values of 2 and 3 are only useful for versions of the BlueCore hardware starting with BlueCore2-ROM.

In the default configuration, a PIO is held high when active and held low when inactive. In versions of BlueCore from BlueCore3-ROM, this behaviour can be altered by setting PSKEY_CLOCK_REQUEST_FEATURES.


Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_RX_MIN_ATTEN 0x0249 uint16 Default 0
Minimum 0
Maximum 8

Minimum attenuation allowed for receiver

Minimum allowed attenuation for receiver apart from channels 29,30,31,61,62,63. This can be used to improve C/I performance and to improve consistency of receiver sensitivity over frequency range.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_HOST_INTERFACE_PIO_USB 0x0250 uint16 none

USB host interface selection PIO line

The PIO line used for forcing the host interface to be USB. The absence of this key, or the value 0xFFFF, indicates that this feature is not in use.

The interface to the host is normally set by PSKEY_HOST_INTERFACE. If this key is set then the specified PIO line is checked at boot time, and if it is asserted (high) then the host interface is set to USB, overriding the setting of PSKEY_HOST_INTERFACE.

The other host transport related persistent store keys must be set appropriately for both the default (probably BCSP) and USB transports.

If PSKEY_HOST_INTERFACE_PIO_H4 is also valid, and both PIO lines are asserted (or they are the same line), this key takes precedence.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_DEEP_SLEEP_CLEAR_RTS 0x0252 bool FALSE

Deep sleep clears the UART RTS line

This key is used for deep sleep with the BCSP and H5 host transports only. If TRUE, the chip clears the RTS line (i.e. sets it high) when it enters deep sleep, and (depending on the state of the UART) may reset it afterwards if it is ready to receive.

If hardware flow control is in effect on the remote host, setting the key causes the remote UART not to transmit packets while the chip is in deep sleep. Therefore it is not possible to use the effect of BCSP retransmissions to wake the chip. Usually, therefore, this key will be used in combination with PSKEY_DEEP_SLEEP_WAKE_CTS.

(Type bool is fundamentally a uint16 with values 0 and 1 mapping to FALSE and TRUE.)


Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_DEEP_SLEEP_PIO_WAKE 0x0255 uint16 Default 16
Maximum 16

PIO line to wake the chip from deep sleep

The number of a PIO line, 0 to 15, which will cause the chip to wake from deep sleep. This use does not preclude the use of the same PIO line as an ordinary input. However, a PIO which is usually configured as an output may not be used. If the setting is out of range, no PIO line will be used. The wake-up is triggered by the level of the line being held high for at least 1 millisecond, not by the rising or falling edge.

If the chip notices it has been woken, and it is configured to use the UART, it will remain out of deep sleep for at least the period given by PSKEY_UART_SLEEP_TIMEOUT. This is because it cannot distinguish wakeups from the two sources. Otherwise, the chip may return to deep sleep as soon as there is no task to be performed.

If the VM is configured to use a PIO line as an interrupt source, the chip will automatically be woken from deep sleep on that line, so this key is not usually required. It may still be used; however, the chip may generate interrupts on the PIO line set by this key, since it does not discriminate between individual PIO lines.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_MODULE_ID 0x0259 uint32 0

Module serial number

A serial number for the module. This number may be allocated by the module manufacturer to track production, etc. This value is not used by any on-chip code and is for manufacturer information only.

The firmware makes no use of this key's value.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_MODULE_DESIGN 0x025a uint16 0

Module design ID

An identifier of the Bluetooth module design. This is allocated by the module manufacturer, so the combination of this key and PSKEY_MODULE_MANUFACTURER should be enough to specify a hardware module design.

This value will normally be independent of firmware identifiers which are used to distinguish various builds of the module's software.

The firmware makes no use of this key's value.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_MODULE_SECURITY_CODE 0x025c uint16[] none

Module security code

When the module is intended to be used with certain host-side applications or stacks, this key is set to an encrypted value.

The host-side application may subsequently check the value of this key to determine whether or not it is licensed to run with the module.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_VM_DISABLE 0x025d bool FALSE

VM disable

If TRUE, the VM will not be started when the chip boots. If FALSE, VM operation is normal.

(Type bool is fundamentally a uint16 with values 0 and 1 mapping to FALSE and TRUE.)


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_MOD_MANUF0 0x025e uint16[] none

Module manufacturer data 0

Keys PSKEY_MOD_MANUF0 to PSKEY_MOD_MANUF9 are for use by module manufactuers. The firmware makes no use of these PSKeys' contents.

Keys PSKEY_MOD_MANUF0 to PSKEY_MOD_MANUF4 are protected against DFU; they are never included in uploads, and are ignored in downloads. This makes them suitable for storing module specific or sensitive information; use keys in the range PSKEY_MOD_MANUF5 to PSKEY_MOD_MANUF9 if such protection is not required.

Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_USB_PIO_DETACH 0x02ce uint16 Default none
Minimum 0
Maximum 15

USB detach/attach PIO line

This PS key sets the PIO line used for USB detach/attach signalling. Any of the first 16 PIOs (numbered 0-15) may be used. The absence of this key indicates that this feature is not in use.

When the PIO specified in this PSKEY goes high, the BlueCore will enter the USB detached state. Conversely when the PIO line goes low BlueCore will enter the USB attached state.

This value is only used if the chip is presenting its USB interface. See the description of PSKEY_HOST_INTERFACE.

This key can only be set to a value above 7 in BlueCore firmware versions 23f and greater.


Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_USB_PIO_WAKEUP 0x02cf uint16 Default none
Minimum 0
Maximum 15

USB wakeup PIO line

This PS key sets the PIO line used for USB wakeup signalling in detach mode. Any of the first 16 PIOs (numbered 0-15) may be used. The absence of this key indicates that this feature is not in use.

When BlueCore is in the USB detached state and has data to send to the host it will raise the PIO specified in this key for a duration of PSKEY_USB_PIO_WAKE_TIMEOUT to signal to the host.

This value is only used if the chip is presenting its USB interface. See the description of PSKEY_HOST_INTERFACE.

This key can only be set to a value above 7 in BlueCore firmware versions 23f and greater.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_USB_PIO_PULLUP 0x02d0 uint16 USB_PULLUP_INTERNAL

USB D+ pullup PIO line

This PS key sets the PIO line used to control the pull-up resistor on the USB D+ line. The absence of this key in the persistent storage indicates that this feature is not in use.

This value is only used if the chip is presenting its USB interface. See the description of PSKEY_HOST_INTERFACE.

On BlueCore, there are 16 PIO lines, 0 to 15 (depending on package type), but 12 to 15 are not available for the USB pullup.

Alternatively an internal pullup can be used by setting this key to the value 'Use internal pullup', which is also the default value.

If value 'No pullup' is selected then the firmware will not apply a pullup, in this case it is intended that the pullup will be controlled by a VM application.

Allowed Values
USB_PULLUP_PIO_0 0 Use PIO 0
USB_PULLUP_PIO_1 1 Use PIO 1
USB_PULLUP_PIO_2 2 Use PIO 2
USB_PULLUP_PIO_3 3 Use PIO 3
USB_PULLUP_PIO_4 4 Use PIO 4
USB_PULLUP_PIO_5 5 Use PIO 5
USB_PULLUP_PIO_6 6 Use PIO 6
USB_PULLUP_PIO_7 7 Use PIO 7
USB_PULLUP_PIO_8 8 Use PIO 8
USB_PULLUP_PIO_9 9 Use PIO 9
USB_PULLUP_PIO_10 10 Use PIO 10
USB_PULLUP_PIO_11 11 Use PIO 11
USB_PULLUP_INTERNAL 16 Use internal pullup
USB_PULLUP_NONE 65534 No pullup

Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_USB_PIO_VBUS 0x02d1 uint16 none

USB VBus detection PIO Line

This PS key sets the PIO line used for USB VBus detection. Any of the first 16 PIOs (numbered 0-15) may be used. In addition, for Bluecore variants with the relevant battery charger hardware, VDD_CHG can be selected instead of a PIO line. The absence of this key indicates that this feature is not in use.

If specifying a PIO, the PIO line should be attached to the USB VBus line. BlueCore then uses the level of this PIO to implement USB attach (when VBus goes high) and detach (when VBus goes low) in the firmware. If specifying VDD_CHG, the VDD_CHG pin will already be connected to USB VBus, and this avoids having to tie up a PIO pin. VDD_CHG can still be used if PSKEY_CHARGER_DISABLE is set to TRUE.

This key is only used if the chip is presenting its USB interface. See the description of PSKEY_HOST_INTERFACE.

This key can only be set to use a PIO above 7 in BlueCore firmware versions 23f and greater.

This key can only be set to use VDD_CHG for Bluecore variants with the relevant battery charger hardware in BlueCore firmware versions 24 and greater.

Allowed Values
USB_VBUS_PIO_0 0 Use PIO 0
USB_VBUS_PIO_1 1 Use PIO 1
USB_VBUS_PIO_2 2 Use PIO 2
USB_VBUS_PIO_3 3 Use PIO 3
USB_VBUS_PIO_4 4 Use PIO 4
USB_VBUS_PIO_5 5 Use PIO 5
USB_VBUS_PIO_6 6 Use PIO 6
USB_VBUS_PIO_7 7 Use PIO 7
USB_VBUS_PIO_8 8 Use PIO 8
USB_VBUS_PIO_9 9 Use PIO 9
USB_VBUS_PIO_10 10 Use PIO 10
USB_VBUS_PIO_11 11 Use PIO 11
USB_VBUS_PIO_12 12 Use PIO 12
USB_VBUS_PIO_13 13 Use PIO 13
USB_VBUS_PIO_14 14 Use PIO 14
USB_VBUS_PIO_15 15 Use PIO 15
USB_VBUS_VDD_CHG 65534 Use VDD_CHG (battery charger)

Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_USB_PIO_WAKE_TIMEOUT 0x02d2 uint16 Default 0
Minimum 0
Maximum 7

Timeout for assertion of USB PIO wake signal

The number of seconds for which the PIO wake signal will be asserted following the generation of data that is to be transmitted to the host when the BlueCore is in the USB detached state. The timeout is reset each time new data is generated.

If this value is 0, the signal is asserted indefinitely (or until the host de-asserts detach).

This key is useful for hosts that are sometimes unable to respond to the wake signal (e.g. laptops when their lids are closed). If wake is asserted when the host cannot process wake and kept asserted until it is able to process the signal, then the host could be woken up to receive an event which is out of date. The host will, of course, have to process any old events when it does reconnect to a device following a wake timeout.

This value is only used if the chip is presenting its USB interface. See the description of PSKEY_HOST_INTERFACE.


Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_USB_PIO_RESUME 0x02d3 uint16 Default none
Minimum 0
Maximum 15

PIO signal used in place of bus resume

The PIO line used to signal that the USB host wakeup from suspend. Any of the first 16 PIOs (numbered 0-15) may be used. The absence of this key indicates that this feature is not in use.

PIO resume is used in place of the bus resume signal for hosts that are unable to respond to the bus signal during suspend e.g. PDAs that power-down the root hub in suspend.

The PIO line is high to indicate that the host should resume, low otherwise. It remains asserted until activity is restored on the USB.

Setting this PS key is sufficient to enable this feature; no notice is taken of the remote wakeup setting of PSKEY_USB_ATTRIBUTES nor of whether the host has enabled remote wakeup.

PSKEY_USB_PIO_RESUME is mutually exclusive with PSKEY_USB_PIO_WAKEUP - both can be enabled simultaneously and assigned to the same PIO pin.

This value is only used if the chip is presenting its USB interface. See the description of PSKEY_HOST_INTERFACE.

This key can only be set to a value above 7 in BlueCore firmware versions 23f and greater.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_USB_BT_SCO_IF_CLASS_CODES 0x02d4 usbclass 0xe0, 0x01, 0x01

USB Bluetooth SCO interface class codes

Three bytes giving the class information for the USB "Interface Descriptor" (as defined in Table 9.9 of version 1.1 of the USB specification and in Table 9.12 (section 9.6.5) of version 2.0 of the USB specification) which contains the SCO endpoints.

This PS key enables different class codes to be used for the BT SCO interface from the main BT interface (which contains the control, event and acl endpoints and whose class codes are given by PSKEY_USB_BT_IF_CLASS_CODES). The advantage of this is that the host OS can load different drivers to communicate with each of the interfaces. This is expected to be of use for Microsoft's XP OS in which the in-built BT USB driver will not give access to the SCO endpoints.

Type usbclass is held as a uint16[3]. The three values are held in the lower byte of each of the array in the order:

        { class, subclass, protocol }.

Default value maps to:
    { WIRELESS_CONTROLLER, RF_CONTROLLER, BLUETOOTH_PROGRAMMING }.

This value is only used if the chip is presenting its USB interface. See the description of PSKEY_HOST_INTERFACE.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_USB_SUSPEND_PIO_LEVEL 0x02d5 uint16 0

USB PIO levels to set when suspended

This description covers PSKEY_USB_SUSPEND_PIO_LEVEL, PSKEY_USB_SUSPEND_PIO_DIR, PSKEY_USB_SUSPEND_PIO_MASK, PSKEY_USB_SUSPEND_PIO_NO_WAKE.

To ensure that the limit on power drawn in suspend mode for a bus-powered device is met, BlueCore usually sets all PIO lines to low. However, this may not always be correct and this set of PS keys allows the configuration to be set.

PSKEY_USB_SUSPEND_PIO_MASK indicates which PIOs should be set when in suspend mode. A 1 in the mask indicates a PIO line to be set according to the corresponding bits in PSKEY_USB_SUSPEND_PIO_LEVEL and PSKEY_USB_SUSPEND_PIO_DIR; a 0 indicates a PIO line that will be left alone.

For each bit that is set to 1 in PSKEY_SUB_SUSPEND_PIO_MASK, a 0 (1) for the corresponding bit in PSKEY_USB_SUSPEND_PIO_LEVEL indicates that the line should be set low (high), and a 0 (1) for the corresponding bit in PSKEY_USB_SUSPEND_PIO_DIR indicates that the line will be set for input (output). Note that from BlueCore2 on if a line is set for input the level is still useful: it determines whether a weak pull-up or pull-down will be applied. Therefore for BlueCore1, PSKEY_USB_SUSPEND_PIO_DIR is not used and any line to be driven is set for output.

Any PIO line configured via PSKEY_USB_PIO_PULLUP is handled separately; the bit does not need to be set in any of these three PSKEYs. The keys apply to a bus-powered USB device only; on a self-powered USB device the PIO lines are not modified in suspend mode.

PSKEY_USB_SUSPEND_PIO_NO_WAKE (see description) provides a mechanism to disable PIO wakeup events during USB suspend.

The names of these keys are misleading as the same facilities are used to handle BCCMDVARID_WARM_HALT and BCCMDVARID_COLD_HALT, regardless of the host transport.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting

Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_USB_SUSPEND_PIO_MASK 0x02d7 uint16 0xffff

Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_USB_STRING_DESCRIPTORS_MAP 0x02da uint16[] none

USB string descriptors map

This key maps USB string descriptor indexes to the PSKEY numbers containing the string descriptors for those indexes. String descriptors are described in section 9.6.7 of the USB2.0 specification.

Each uint16 pair maps a string index to a PSKEY number. The format of this key is therefore:

 {string_index, pskey_number}, {string_index, pskey_number}, ...

If string descriptor index 8 is to be mapped to the string contained in PSKEY_USB_STRING_DESCRIPTOR0 (assume it's PSKEY number is 0x02db) and string descriptor index 6 is to be mapped to the string contained in PSKEY_USB_STRING_DESCRIPTOR15 (assume it's PSKEY number is 0x02ea), then PSKEY_USB_STRING_DESCRIPTORS_MAP would be set as follows:

{8, 02db} , {6, 02ea}

The PSKEY_USB_STRING_DESCRIPTORn keys were created to provide a convenient set of keys in which to store USB string descriptor strings.

Only string descriptor index in the range 5..255 can be used as 1..4 are reserved.

Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_USB_SUSPEND_PIO_NO_WAKE 0x02ff uint16 0x0000

USB PIO lines not to be used for waking up in suspend

This key indicates which input PIOs should not be allowed to generate a deep sleep wakeup event.

Each bit that is set to 1 in PSKEY_USB_SUSPEND_PIO_NO_WAKE indicates that the line should not be allowed to generate a deep sleep wakeup event during USB suspend.

Note that the wakeup event is generated only if the PIO lines have already been configured to do so using either PSKEY_DEEP_SLEEP_PIO_WAKE or the VM.

Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_RADIOTEST_ATTEN_INIT 0x0320 uint16 Default 0
Minimum 0
Maximum 15

Radio test initial attenuator

Initial value of the attenuator setting for radio tests. This is ignored by the main Bluetooth stack.


Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_RADIOTEST_FIRST_TRIM_TIME 0x0326 TIME Default 5 * SECOND
Minimum 0
Maximum 300 * SECOND

IQ first calibration period in test

The time from the start of a test till the first IQ trim auto-calibration is done. A value of 0 disables the automatic calibration completely during the test. A calibration is still done before the test starts.


Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_RADIOTEST_SUBSEQUENT_TRIM_TIME 0x0327 TIME Default 0
Minimum 0
Maximum 300 * SECOND

IQ subsequent calibration period in test

In normal operation, the chip schedules regular trims of the IQ block to prevent degradation of the radio performance. These are placed so as to avoid interfering with normal radio traffic. This is not possible in radiotest mode when the transmissions are back to back, hence this key exists to choose the most suitable behaviour.

Once the first IQ trim auto calibration is done in test mode, then subsequent trims are done at regular intervals with the period being given by this key, which is a time in microseconds. If the value is 0 then no subsequent trim is performed.

If PSKEY_RADIOTEST_FIRST_TRIM_TIME is 0 then no trims are done during the test regardless of the setting of this key.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_RADIOTEST_LO_LVL_TRIM_ENABLE 0x0328 bool TRUE

LO_LVL calibration enable

If IQ trim is enabled (PSKEY_IQ_TRIM_ENABLE), enables trimming of the value for the register ANA_LO_ENABLE; otherwise, has no effect. This trimming takes place before the start of each test.

(Type bool is fundamentally a uint16 with values 0 and 1 mapping to FALSE and TRUE.)

Allowed Values
TRUE 1 Enabled
FALSE 0 Disabled

Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_RADIOTEST_DISABLE_MODULATION 0x032c bool FALSE

Disable modulation during radiotest transmissions

If enabled, do not use modulation during any of the radiotest_txdata routines. Clearly, this is no use for transmitting packets; it is present to provide a low level way of showing the radio carrier behaviour.

Has no effect on any other function.

(Type bool is fundamentally a uint16 with values 0 and 1 mapping to FALSE and TRUE.)

PSKEY_MR_TX_IF_ATTEN_OFF_TEMP 0x0394 int16 -20

TX IF atten off temperature when using EDR.

This PSKEY controls the temperature above which the TX IF attentuator is turned off when using EDR. The units of this key are degrees Celsius. The value should correspond to the discontinuity in the temperature values in PSKEY_TEMPERATURE_VS_DELTA_TX_BB_MR_PAYLOAD and PSKEY_TEMPERATURE_VS_DELTA_TX_BB_MR_HEADER.

(The abbreviation MR for Medium Rate is used consistently in place of EDR for Enhanced Data Rate throughout the PS keys as many were introduced before the abbreviation EDR came into use.)


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_CHARGER_CURRENT 0x039b uint16 0x0

Set the charger current

Certain devices from BlueCore4-Headset onwards allow a range of charger currents to be used. The actual current depends on the device type and the charge state of the battery. This key sets the default fast charge current to use, which is dependent on the size and type of battery. The setting to use can be determined from the battery and BlueCore device datasheets.

On BlueCore7 and later devices, the key specifies the approximate charger current in mA. On earlier devices, the value range is 0-15 and values greater than 15 are not supported. Consult the datasheet for your BlueCore device for more detailed information.


Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_PIO_WAKEUP_STATE 0x039f uint16 Default 0xFFFF
Minimum 0
Maximum 0xFFFF

PIO deep sleep wake up state

Controls the state for each PIO line (0 to 15) that will wake the chip from deep sleep. Each bit corresponds to a PIO line. Setting a bit high will result in the chip waking when that line goes high, setting the bit low will cause the chip to wake when the line goes low. The PIO lines must already have been configured to wake the chip using either PSKEY_DEEP_SLEEP_PIO_WAKE or the VM.

This PSKEY should only be changed on advice from CSR.

Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_TEMPERATURE_VS_DELTA_TX_BB_MR_PAYLOAD 0x03aa temperature_calibration[] { -40, 31}, { 20, 0}

Temperature for a given TX_BB in EDR payload

The value is a table in the same format as PSKEY_TEMPERATURE_VS_DELTA_INTERNAL_PA. The values of the table (even-numbered 16-bit words) in this case are an adjustment applied separately to both the top nybbles of PSKEY_TX_FILTER_CONFIG when transmitting the payload of a packet at Enhanced Data Rate; hence they must lie in the range -15 to 15. The adjusted nybbles will be limited to the range 0 to 15.

Note that, using the default values, there is a discontinuity in the values in this key at 55 deg C (pre-BlueCore5) or -20 deg C, which corresponds to switching off the TX IF attenuator (see PSKEY_MR_TX_IF_ATTEN_OFF_TEMP). Since BlueCore can only measure temperatures at a resolution of 1 deg C, this is represented by two consecutive values at 54 and 55 deg C or -21 and -20 deg C.

(The abbreviation MR for Medium Rate is used consistently in place of EDR for Enhanced Data Rate throughout the PS keys as many were introduced before the abbreviation EDR came into use.)


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_TEMPERATURE_VS_DELTA_TX_BB_MR_HEADER 0x03ab temperature_calibration[] { -40, 21}, { 20, 0}

Temperature for a given TX_BB in EDR header

The value is a table in the same format as PSKEY_TEMPERATURE_VS_DELTA_INTERNAL_PA. The values of the table (even-numbered 16-bit words) in this case are an adjustment applied separately to both the top nybbles of PSKEY_TX_FILTER_CONFIG when transmitting the header of a packet at Enhanced Data Rate; hence they must lie in the range -15 to 15. The adjusted nybbles will be limited to the range 0 to 15.

Note that, using the default values, there is a discontinuity in the values in this key at 55 deg C (pre-BlueCore5) or -20 deg C, which corresponds to switching off the TX IF attenuator (see PSKEY_MR_TX_IF_ATTEN_OFF_TEMP). Since BlueCore can only measure temperatures at a resolution of 1 deg C, this is represented by two consecutive values at 54 and 55 deg C or -21 and -20 deg C.

(The abbreviation MR for Medium Rate is used consistently in place of EDR for Enhanced Data Rate throughout the PS keys as many were introduced before the abbreviation EDR came into use.)


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_TEMPERATURE_VS_DELTA_INTERNAL_PA_CLASS1 0x03ae temperature_calibration[] none

Temperature for given internal PA adjustment

Table in the same form as PSKEY_TEMPERATURE_VS_DELTA_INTERNAL_PA used when transmitting at class 1 powers. The value of this key is only used when the class 1 bit is set in PSKEY_LC_ENHANCED_POWER_TABLE.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_UART_CONFIG2 0x03b1 uint8 2

The UART Sampling point

Configuration for UART rx sampling point in case there are any problems with fast (just below 4Mbps) UARTs.

Currently 2 bits are defined. Bit 0 is prefetch, Bit 1 is RX offset. The default value is 2, ie RX offset enabled, prefetch disabled.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_MR_PIO_CONFIG 0x03b2 uint16 0

PIO line asserted in class1 operation to avoid PA

Additional configuration for PIO lines used for hardware from BlueCore4 which supports Enhanced Data Rate (EDR). Each bit specifies a different feature.

Currently only Bit 0 is defined. If it is set, any use of PIO 1 for activating an external power amplifier (as configured by PSKEY_TXRX_PIO_CONTROL) is tied to the enhanced data rate packet transmission: the PIO line goes high when the modulation scheme switches to EDR's Phase Shift Keying (PSK). If it is clear, the default behaviour obtains: the PIO goes high when the packet header starts. This bit is mostly useful for test purposes.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_TX_AVOID_PA_CLASS1_PIO 0x03b3 uint16 0xFFFF

PIO line asserted in class1 operation to avoid PA

This PS key is only used for class 1 operation, i.e. when PSKEY_LC_ENHANCED_POWER_TABLE has entries with the class 1 bit set. If no entry in the table is set for class 1 operation, the value of this PS key is ignored.

The value gives a PIO line which will be asserted during a transmission when the external power amplifier is not in use. The value 1 is not allowed, as it is always used to activate the external PA. Any other PIO line may be used. If the value is 0, it indicates that PIO 0 will be used for this purpose, in addition to any use specified by PSKEY_TXRX_PIO_CONTROL during receive operations.

A value greater than 15 indicates that no PIO will be asserted when the external PA is not in use.

Note that the PIO line is asserted by software, so does not have the accuracy of the hardware used for the external PA. However, the PIO is guaranteed to be asserted at least while the radio is in use for transmission.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_INITIAL_PIO_STATE 0x03b5 uint16[2..6] none

Initial state of PIO0 - PIO15 pins

This key may be used to set the initial state of the PIO0-15 pins prior to the VM application running. The key is an array of uint16s which can be considered to have the following structure:-

 struct {
   uint16 mask;
   uint16 direction;
   uint16 level;
   uint16 bias;
   uint16 buskeep_en;
   uint16 disable_pull;
 }

Each word within the structure can be considered to be an array of bits corresponding to individual PIO pins.

The mask word is used to control which PIO pins are controlled by this key. Note that PIOs which are assigned to firmware functions (including those masked by PSKEY_PIO_PROTECT_MASK) are also masked out.

The direction word is used to control pin direction:-
 0 = input
 1 = output

The level word is optional and controls pin output levels:-
 0 = low
 1 = high

From BlueCore2-External on, for pins set as inputs by the direction word, the corresponding bits in this word determine the direction of a weak pull device (0=pull-down, 1=pull-up). If the word is not present, pins will be set to their default power-on levels.

The bias word is optional and controls the strength of the bias applied to pins configured as input:-
 0 = weak bias
 1 = strong bias

If the word is not present, pins will be set to their default power-on bias strength.

The buskeep_en word is optional and controls whether "bus-keeper" functionality (see PSKEY_BCSP_PULL_CONTROL) is enabled for pins configured as inputs, on chips which support this:-
 0 = bus-keeper disabled
 1 = bus-keeper enabled

If the word is not present, no bus-keepers will be enabled.

The disable_pull word is optional and controls whether the internal pull device is disabled (see PSKEY_BCSP_PULL_CONTROL) for pins configured as inputs, on chips which support this. (These bits have no effect on pins configured as outputs.)
 0 = pull device enabled
 1 = pull device disabled

If the word is not present, pull devices will be enabled. NOTE: disabling pull devices when pins are not driven externally can lead to excessive current consumption and potentially damage the chip.

Example -------

To set PIO 3 as an output driving a high signal and PIO 5 as an input with strong-bias set the key to (0x0028,0x0008,0x0008,0x0020).

 mask = 0x0028 # (1<<5 | 1<<3)
 direction = 0x0008 # (1<<3)
 level = 0x0008 # (1<<3)
 bias = 0x0020 # (1<<5)


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_CLOCK_REQUEST_FEATURES 0x03b6 uint16 0

Clock request is tristated if enabled

This key is only applicable if the value of PSKEY_CLOCK_REQUEST_ENABLE is non-zero.

The clock request PIO can be configured to be active high or active low. In an inactive state, it can be tristated or driven as an output by BlueCore.

Bit 0 of this PSKEY inverts the polarity of the PIO when not tristated.
 When it is set, the PIO is active low.
 When it is clear, the PIO is active high.

When Bit 1 is set, PIO is tristated when the clock request is inactive. When Bit 1 is clear, PIO is a driven output when the clock request is inactive.

The default behaviour is that the PIO is active high and always driven.

The key is available from BlueCore3-ROM, but has no effect on BlueCore3-Multimedia. BlueCore3-Multimedia has the clock request line but this cannot be configured to either be inverted or tristated.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_LC_USE_THROTTLING 0x03b8 bool 1

Adjust packet selection on packet error rate

Allow the LC to select the packet type it chooses depending on the packet error rate. Setting this to FALSE makes the LC select packet size on data size only.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_USB_DONT_RESET_BOOTMODE_ON_HOST_RESET 0x03b9 bool 0

Don't reset bootmode if USB host resets

If a USB reset is received after a device has been enumerated and the Bluecore is in a bootmode other than the default, the USB subsystem will force a reset into the default bootmode unless this key is set to TRUE.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_MR_TX_CONFIG2 0x03ba uint16 0xaa07

TX filter configuration used for enhanced data rate

Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
