TX filter configuration used for enhanced data rate

Configures the transmit filter used in Enhanced Data Rate packets for optimum modulation. For CSR use only.


Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_I2C_CONFIG 0x03be uint16 Default 0x0000
Minimum 0x0000
Maximum 0x0001

I2C configuration

Configures the I2C bus. The default value of this PSKey configures the I2C bus for maximally-portable use, i.e. standard mode with long timeouts, suitable for slow I2C EEPROMs.

If Bit 0 is set, the I2C bus is configured for fast mode. All other devices on the bus (i.e. all slave devices) must obey the fast mode I2C specification. Note that in this mode the firmware does not have timeouts for SCL stretching -- the firmware will block while SCL is held low by the slave.

Also note that fast mode is currently not implemented for signalling I2C operations such as (re)starts, stops and read acknowledgements; these will be performed as if in standard mode.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_USB_VM_CONTROL 0x03c0 bool 0

VM application will supply USB descriptors

Some VM applications such as the HID-proxy or USB cable-replacement dongle can supply their own USB descriptors. When using such an application, this key must be set to TRUE to ensure that the firmware does not attempt to register the default HCI descriptors.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_DEEP_SLEEP_USE_EXTERNAL_CLOCK 0x03c3 bool FALSE

Deep sleep uses external 32 kHz clock source

Versions of BlueCore from BlueCore3 can take a 32 kHz clock input to act as a timing source when the chip is in deep sleep. (This is referred to as the slow clock.) Its frequency must be stable to at least 250 parts per million, and it must be continuously present while the BlueCore is powered. Its use is enabled by setting this key to TRUE.

The source of this clock varies:
 - On BlueCore4 and prior, the clock input must be presented on AIO0;
 - On BlueCore5-FM and BlueCore6-ROM, the clock input can be
   presented either on a dedicated SLEEP_CLK pin (the default), or on
   AIO0; selection is via PSKEY_DEEP_SLEEP_EXTERNAL_CLOCK_SOURCE;
 - On BlueCore7-FM the clock input must be presented on the
   dedicated SLEEP_CLK pin.
 - Some parts after BlueCore7-FM have no dedicated SLEEP_CLK pin but
   use one of a small selection of PIOs for the clock input, see
   PSKEY_DEEP_SLEEP_EXTERNAL_CLOCK_SOURCE_PIO

The clock does not have to be exactly 32 kHz; anything within a few percent (including 30 kHz) is useful. The firmware will calibrate this external slow clock against the standard 20 ppm clock (as supplied by crystal or TCXO) at startup. If PSKEY_DEEP_SLEEP_STATE is set to DEEP_SLEEP_ALWAYS_ACCURATE, the firmware will assume the external slow clock does not need subsequent calibration, saving extra power.

If the worst-case accuracy of the supplied clock is significantly better than 250 parts per million, PSKEY_DEVICE_DRIFT can usefully be set to that accuracy. This allows a slave in low power mode to turn on its radio for less time when attempting to resynchronise with its master. The worse-case accuracy of the supplied clock should not be any worse than 250 ppm for compliance with the Bluetooth specification.

On devices which use the external 32 kHz clock for purposes other than timing deep sleep -- for instance, for the FM radio(s) on BlueCore5-FM and BlueCore7-FM -- this key must be set to enable calibration of the clock which is required for those uses. (If an external 32 kHz clock is present for such uses, it is almost certainly desirable to use it for sleep timing as well.)

(Type bool is fundamentally a uint16 with values 0 and 1 mapping to FALSE and TRUE.)


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_SCHED_THROTTLE_TIMEOUT 0x03c4 TIME 500 * MILLISECOND

Scheduler performance control.

This key modifies the behaviour of the Bluecore's scheduler. It should only be configured on advice from CSR.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_RSSI_CORRECTION 0x03c5 int8 0

RSSI correction factor.

The BlueCore (from BlueCore2-Ext chip version onwards) is able to measure the signal strength of packets received from air. This measurement is of the signal strength at the input to the chip rather than at the input to the module i.e. it does account for any attenuation or gain provided by external components such as the antenna or a LNA.

This PSKey specifies a value in dB that will be added to the BlueCore's RSSI reading to correct for external components.

In builds prior to 19, this PSKey only affects the RSSI values reported in 'inquiry response with RSSI' HCI events; it does not affect the RSSI value reported via the HCI_Read_RSSI command. In 19 builds and upwards, this key affects all RSSI values reported by the chip.


Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_RX_ATTEN_UPDATE_RATE 0x03c9 uint16 Default 2
Minimum 0
Maximum 15

Receiver attenuation update rate

This sets the rate at which the automatic gain control updates the receiver's attenuation.

Only useful from BlueCore3.

A value of 4 in PSKEY_RX_ATTEN_BACKOFF implies PSKEY_RX_ATTEN_UPDATE_RATE must be at least 2: if one key is changed, the other should be changed in direct proportion.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_ONCHIP_HCI_CLIENT 0x03cc bool 0

HCI traffic routed internally

This key controls the routing of HCI traffic. For a vanilla 'HCI' firmware build this key should be set to FALSE (0). For a firmware build that incorporates upper stack layers, this key should be set to TRUE (1).


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_INITIAL_BOOTMODE 0x03cd int16 none

Initial device bootmode

The firmware is capable of switching between a number of different 'bootmodes'. Each bootmode presents a different view of the persistent store, with some keys being overridden by bootmode-specific values. A device can support a maximum of 8 bootmodes. If this key is present the device will enter the specified bootmode after a cold reset. If the key is not present, bootmode 0 will be used.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_RX_DYNAMIC_LVL_OFFSET 0x03d4 uint16 0

Receiver dynamic level offset depending on channel

The value of this key is added to the receiver level to optimise certain channels during reception.

For BlueCore5 and below It consists of four four-bit fields. Bits 0 to 3 control the behaviour at resonance, bits 4 to 7 one channel away, bits 8 to 11 two channels away, and bits 12 to 15 three channels away.

For BlueCore7 and above Non zero value indicates use of maximum LNA bias for deaf frequency (i.e. channels multiple of reference frequency)


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_TEMPERATURE_VS_DELTA_TX_BB 0x03d8 temperature_calibration[] { -40, 38}, { 20, 0}

Temperature for a given TX_BB adjustment

The value is a table in the same format as PSKEY_TEMPERATURE_VS_DELTA_INTERNAL_PA. The values of the table (even-numbered 16-bit words) in this case are an adjustment applied separately to both the top nybbles of PSKEY_TX_FILTER_CONFIG; hence they must lie in the range -15 to 15. The adjusted nybbles will be limited to the range 0 to 15.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_TEMPERATURE_VS_DELTA_TX_PRE_LVL 0x03d9 temperature_calibration[] none

Temperature for a given TX_PRE_LVL adjustment

The value is a table in the same format as PSKEY_TEMPERATURE_VS_DELTA_INTERNAL_PA. The values of the table (even-numbered 16-bit words) in this case are an adjustment applied to PSKEY_TX_PRE_LVL which should be in the range -15 to 15. The adjusted value will be limited to the range 0 to 15.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_TEMPERATURE_VS_DELTA_INTERNAL_PA 0x03da temperature_calibration[] { -40, -7}, { 20, 0}

Temperature for given internal PA adjustment

The value consists of a table of pairs of 16-bit signed values, as many pairs as necessary. Each pair is in a similar format to PSKEY_TEMPERATURE_CALIBRATION: the first value is a temperature in degrees Celsius, while in this case the second is a signed correction to be made to the internal PA setting at that temperature. The value will be interpolated linearly between those settings, but will not be extrapolated beyond the end of the temperature range. The temperatures should increase monotonically, but the corrections at each temperature need not.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_DEEP_SLEEP_CORRECTION_FACTOR 0x03dc int16 0

Deep sleep clock correction factor

In deep sleep, BlueCore has a low power oscillator circuit which is used to keep time. Different variants of the chip have slightly different behaviour. This key allows the correction for the chip to be tweaked: lower (signed) values make the clock run slower, and higher values make it run faster. This should only need to be changed for different hardware; therefore, the value should only be altered on advice from CSR.

The value is not applied if PSKEY_DEEP_SLEEP_USE_EXTERNAL_CLOCK is TRUE as the external slow clock will not have the same systematic behaviour.


Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_CLOCK_STARTUP_DELAY 0x03dd uint16 Default 0
Maximum 31

Clock startup delay in milliseconds

On waking from deep sleep, BlueCore expects an accurate external clock supplied to the chip to be stable to 20 ppm within, by default, 5 milliseconds. For configurations that use the clock request line (see PSKEY_CLOCK_REQUEST_ENABLE), this is measured from the clock request line being asserted. If this is not the case this PSKEY needs to be changed to an appropriate value.

This PSKEY provides a time value in nominal milliseconds, from 1 to 31 inclusive. BlueCore will wait for this time for the clock to stabilise. The special value zero (the default) is identical to using a value of 5, and causes a delay of 5 milliseconds to be used. Setting a value larger than that required for the clock to become stable will result in slightly less efficient power consumption on entry to and exit from deep sleep. Setting a value that is too small will result in erratic behaviour.

On builds that support it, PSKEY_CLOCK_STARTUP_DELAY_FINE_ADJUSTMENT may be further used to add fine granularity to the wake up delay. To allow for very short delays, if the fine adjustment is non-zero, setting PSKEY_CLOCK_STARTUP_DELAY to zero no longer gives a 5 ms delay: see the description of PSKEY_CLOCK_STARTUP_DELAY_FINE_ADJUSTMENT for details.

Note: on the BlueCore2-ROM this key has no effect if the value is less than 6 milliseconds, or if no clock request line is in use.


Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_FORCE_16MHZ_REF_PIO 0x03e1 uint16 Default none
Minimum 0

PIO line to force 16 MHz reference to be assumed

The number of a PIO line, 0 to 15, which will cause the value of PSKEY_ANA_FREQ to be ignored and a 16 MHz reference to be assumed instead. A value of 0xFFFF, or absence of a value, indicates the feature is not to be used.

This is useful in ROM builds which may set the PSKEY_ANA_FREQ default for a non-16 MHz reference (eg. 13 or 26 MHz, as commonly used in GSM phones). It allows correct operation with modules that use a 16 MHz crystal instead. Without this facility it would not be possible to make a host connection at a standard UART baud rate or with USB for modules that use a 16 MHz crystal.

Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_PMALLOC_EXTRA 0x215e uint16[]

Extra pmalloc sizes array

This key specifies memory pools which are not regarded as essential for operation of the firmware. The format of the key is the same as that of PSKEY_PMALLOC_BASE.

This key should not be altered except on specific advice from CSR.

See the description of PSKEY_PMALLOC_BASE for details of the memory allocator.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_PMALLOC_APP 0x215f uint16[] none

VM application pmalloc sizes array

This key specifies the memory pools created for use by the VM. It is only used in firmware which contains a VM. The format of the key is the same as that of PSKEY_PMALLOC_BASE.

Altering this key allows users to create pmalloc blocks for use by the VM. Typically, these blocks will be larger than those which the firmware provides by default. As the total size of the memory available to the pmalloc allocator is fixed, altering this key may involve altering PSKEY_MAX_ACLS or PSKEY_MAX_SCOS to claim back some memory. See the description of PSKEY_PMALLOC_BASE for details.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_PMALLOC_PER_SCO 0x2160 uint16[]

Per SCO pmalloc sizes array

This key specifies the memory pools used by a single SCO link. The format of the key is the same as that of PSKEY_PMALLOC_BASE.

This key should not be altered except on specific advice from CSR.

Reducing PSKEY_MAX_SCOS allows the memory claimed by a SCO link to be put to other uses (for example, use by VM applications). See the description of PSKEY_PMALLOC_BASE for more details.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_PMALLOC_PER_ACL 0x2161 uint16[]

Per ACL pmalloc sizes array

This key specifies the memory pools used by a single ACL link. The format of the key is the same as that of PSKEY_PMALLOC_BASE.

This key should not be altered except on specific advice from CSR.

Reducing PSKEY_MAX_ACLS allows the memory claimed by an ACL link to be put to other uses (for example, use by VM applications). See the description of PSKEY_PMALLOC_BASE for more details.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_PMALLOC_BASE 0x2162 uint16[]

Base pmalloc sizes array

The pmalloc pool memory manager is used throughout the firmware and by VM applications. It is described briefly here, and in more detail in the application note CS-128085-AN "Configuring the BlueCore memory allocator".

The way in which its raw RAM block is fragmented is specified by PSKEYS:
 * PSKEY_PMALLOC_BASE
 * PSKEY_PMALLOC_PER_ACL
 * PSKEY_PMALLOC_PER_SCO
 * PSKEY_PMALLOC_APP (when the firmware supports VM applications)
 * PSKEY_PMALLOC_EXTRA

Each of these keys is an array of pairs of uint16s: {uint16 el_size, uint16 n_elements}. Each pair describes a pool containing n_elements each of size el_size (in 16-bit words).

In the case of PSKEY_PMALLOC_PER_ACL, the key specifies the pools used by a single ACL link. The n_elements value for each pool in this key is multiplied by PSKEY_MAX_ACLS when carving up the raw RAM block. Similarly, the PSKEY_PMALLOC_PER_SCO key is multiplied by PSKEY_MAX_SCOS.

PSKEY_PMALLOC_BASE, PSKEY_PMALLOC_PER_ACL, PSKEY_PMALLOC_PER_SCO and PSKEY_PMALLOC_EXTRA are calculated at firmware build time, and should not be modified except on specific advice from CSR.

PSKEY_PMALLOC_APP has no default value. Customers may add a value which uses some or all of the storage specified in PSKEY_PMALLOC_EXTRA, but usually in a different configuration (typically to produce a few, large pools). Similarly, by reducing PSKEY_MAX_ACLS or PSKEY_MAX_SCOS, the storage used by an instance of PSKEY_PMALLOC_PER_ACL or PSKEY_PMALLOC_PER_SCO may be added to PSKEY_PMALLOC_APP. Hence, it is intended that users will alter PSKEY_PMALLOC_APP and possibly PSKEY_MAX_ACLS and PSKEY_MAX_SCOS if they require larger pools for their VM applications.

The application note CS-128085-AN "Configuring the BlueCore memory allocator" describes the process of setting PSKEY_PMALLOC_APP in more detail. Customers should refer to this app note before altering the PSKEY_PMALLOC_APP key.

Note that the pools specified by a given PSKEY are not reserved for a particular use by the firmware: they join a common set of pools available from the allocator. Hence it is possible for a pool specified by PSKEY_PMALLOC_APP to be taken by the firmware itself if no other pools are available.

Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_I2C_SLOWDOWN 0x216e uint16 Default 10

Maximum 100

I2C slowdown factor times 10

Slow down the I2C by a factor bearing some relation to value / 10, though at higher speeds this will be very approximate. Values below 10 speed up the I2C and are unsafe. Values above 10 slow down I2C.

Only has any effect if I2C_CONFIG is set to 0 (100 kHz, slow mode).

Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_CLOCK_REQUEST_PULL_CONTROL 0x2176 uint16 0x0000

Bus-keeper/pull-disable for clock request

This key configures the enhanced pull device control features present on some BlueCore chips for the clock request input. See PSKEY_BCSP_PULL_CONTROL for more information on the pull device control features.

The bits in this key only have any effect when a clock request is in use, as determined by PSKEY_CLOCK_REQUEST_ENABLE. The selected modes are enabled at boot time and never disabled.

Bit 0 controls "bus-keeper" mode: if this bit is clear (the default), "bus-keeper" mode is never enabled; if set, "bus-keeper" mode is enabled at the appropriate time by the firmware.

Bit 1 controls "pull-disable" mode: if this bit is clear (the default), the pull device is never disabled; if set, the pull device is disabled at the appropriate time by the firmware.

NOTE: incorrect configuration of this key can lead to excessive power consumption and can potentially damage the chip. The default value is safe in this regard.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_RX_SCAN_BIASES 0x2179 uint16[] 0, 0

Bias settings used during Bluetooth scanning

Contains the LNA bias (first word) and RX mixer bias (second word) settings to be used during Bluetooth inquiry and page scans.

When not scanning, the LNA bias is calculated dynamically with a minimum defined by PSKEY_RX_MIN_ATTEN, and the RX mixer bias is taken from PSKEY_RX_AGC_CONFIG.

This key is for CSR use only.

Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_USB_CHARGER_DETECTION_ENABLE 0x2180 uint16 USB_CHARGER_DETECTION_OFF

Enables detection of dedicated USB chargers

This key determines whether the firmware will implement USB charger detection. (Note that this refers to detecting what is at the other end of the USB cable when the device is plugged in, not to be confused with the battery charger hardware on the Bluecore device itself).

If set to 'No charger detection (0)' the firmware will not implement any charger detection. This is the default.

If set to 'Resistive detection (1)' the firmware will use the Resistive Detection Mechanism (see the USB Battery Charging Specification Revision 1.0 section 3.10). This enables the firmware to distinguish between a dedicated charger and a standard host or hub. Note that this detection mechanism has been dropped from the USB Battery Charging Specification Revision 1.2, in order to remain in conformance use Voltage source detection if available.

If set to 'Voltage source detection (2)' the firmware will use the full charger detection procedure as detailed in the USB Battery Charging Specification Revision 1.1 section 3.2. This enables the firmware to distinguish between a standard host or hub, a dedicated charger, and a host or hub charger. This option is only available if the Bluecore device has the necessary hardware (see individual device data sheet). When this option is selected, the firmware will ignore the value of PSKEY_USB_DATA_PLUS_PULL_CONTROL and always act as if PSKEY_USB_DATA_PLUS_PULL_CONTROL has been set to AFTER_CONFIGURATION ('sets D+ when configuration is done').

A VM app can use trap UsbAttachedStatus() to find out to what it is currently attached.

Allowed Values
USB_CHARGER_DETECTION_OFF 0 No charger detection
USB_CHARGER_DETECTION_RESISTIVE 1 Resistive detection
USB_CHARGER_DETECTION_VOLTAGE_SOURCE 2 Voltage source detection

Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_TEMPERATURE_CALIBRATION_10BIT 0x2191 temperature_calibration_10bit 0x0015, 0x020f, 0x0203

Temperature in deg C for a given internal setting

This value must be set to enable temperature compensation. It is used to calibrate the internal thermometer and can be set separately for each individual chip. It consists of three words.

The first word is the calibration temperature in degrees Celsius stored as an int16. The second and third words are uint16.

This key is used on BlueCore7 onwards in place of PSKEY_TEMPERATURE_CALIBRATION, which was used up to and including BlueCore6. All three readings must be made together.

The second and third values are the vref (4) and bandgap_vbe (consult documentation for the correct selector) values as returned from the standard BCCMD adc_read interface.

To turn temperature compensation off, all words should be set to zero. (Note that this must be *three* zero 16-bit words, as zero is an acceptable value for the temperature in degrees Celsius.)

Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_DSP_WRITE_WINDOW 0x2194 bool FALSE

Enable write access from DSP to external memory

When this key is enabled, code loaded onto the DSP is given read and write access through data window 3. This key is only useful if your hardware design includes an external memory device which is accessed from the DSP.

Note that to address an external memory device above 32Mbit in the BlueCore5mm address map, the application will also need to set MISC_EXT_RAM_EN or MISC_EXT_RAM_EN2 in PSKEY_GBL_MISC_ENABLES to enable PIO2 or PIO6 respectively as an additional address line. The application will also need to ensure that PIO line is an output, using PioSetDir from the VM application.

Also note that if either of MISC_EXT_RAM_EN or and MISC_EXT_RAM_EN2 is set in PSKEY_GBL_MISC_ENABLES then the use of PSKEY_SRAM_PIO is rendered useless and the effect would be same as if invalid Sram PIO value has been set in PSKEY_SRAM_PIO i.e., VM application gets failure (NULL return) if attempt is made to use SramMap trap.

Allowed Values
TRUE 1 Enabled
FALSE 0 Disabled

Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_PIO_WAKEUP_STATE2 0x21ba uint16 Default 0xFFFF
Minimum 0
Maximum 0xFFFF

PIO deep sleep wake up state

Controls the state for each PIO line (16 to 31) that will wake the chip from deep sleep. Each bit corresponds to a PIO line. Setting a bit high will result in the chip waking when that line goes high, setting the bit low will cause the chip to wake when the line goes low.

Note that not all chips have more than 16 PIOs, and some that do may not have a full 32. The PIO lines must already have been configured to wake the chip using the VM.


Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_PIO_DEEP_SLEEP_EITHER_LEVEL 0x21bd uint32 Default 0
Minimum 0
Maximum 0xFFFFFFFF

PIO deep sleep on either level

Allows the chip to deep sleep irrespective of the level of the PIO lines. Traditionally BlueCore chips will stay out of deep sleep when any PIO line configured as an input is high. This behaviour can be modified by setting PSKEY_PIO_WAKEUP_STATE so that the chip will stay out of deep sleep when lines are low, but enter deep sleep when the lines are high.

Each bit in this PSKEY corresponds to a PIO line from 0 to 31. Note that 31 PIOs may not be present on all BlueCores. Setting a bit will result that PIO's level having no effect on the chip's deep sleep behaviour; the chip will go into deep sleep if the PIO is high or low. The BlueCore will still wakeup to process changes in PIO levels.

The PIO lines must already have been configured to wake the chip using either PSKEY_DEEP_SLEEP_PIO_WAKE or the VM.

Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_PANIC_ON_FAULT 0x21ce bool FALSE

Panic on encountering fault

When this key is FALSE (as it is by default), when a fault condition is encountered, BlueCore issues a fault report and carries on running. When this key is set to TRUE, BlueCore will instead panic immediately when any fault condition is encountered, with panic code PANIC_ON_FAULT (0x4E).

This is intended as a diagnostic aid for CSR engineers. It should not be enabled except on advice from CSR, and CSR does not recommend setting it in production applications.

Panics and faults are described in the document "HQ Commands", bcore-sp-003P.

(Type bool is fundamentally a uint16 with values 0 and 1 mapping to FALSE and TRUE.)

Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_SLOW_CLOCK_TEMP_HYSTERESIS 0x21d8 uint16 4

Slow clock recal temperature hysteresis

The internal low power oscillator (known as the "slow clock") is recalibrated against the accurate clock when the temperature changes. If the temperature change since the last calibration exceeds the value of this key, another calibration is performed.

The units of this key are degrees Celsius.

Recalibration may be made more sensitive to temperature if the value of PSKEY_SLOW_CLOCK_TEMP_HYSTERESIS_MIN is lower than the value of this key. If a large change in calibration (greater than 200 ppm) is detected, the required temperature change is reduced by steps of 1 degree Celsius until PSKEY_SLOW_CLOCK_TEMP_HYSTERESIS_MIN is reached. If a small change in calibration (less than 100 ppm) is detected, the required temperature change is increased in steps of 1 degree Celsius until PSKEY_SLOW_CLOCK_TEMP_HYSTERESIS is reached.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_EXTERNAL_SLOW_CLOCK_DEFAULT_FREQ 0x21de uint32 524288

Default frequency for external slow clock

Default frequency (in 1/16 Hz) assumed for external 32kHz slow clock. This frequency is assumed if calibration fails, or is turned off (by setting PSKEY_EXTERNAL_SLOW_CLOCK_CALIBRATION_ATTEMPTS to 0).

Source of external 32kHz sleep clock

On some devices an external 32kHz sleep clock can be routed in via a pin or pins and/or internally derived from the fast reference clock. This key controls which of these clock sources is used.

Note that this only affects the clock source used for deep sleep timing, not the clock source to drive the FM radio [if present] etc.

Valid values:
 0: Slow clock input via dedicated CLK32K_IN pin

For a guide to options, see PSKEY_DEEP_SLEEP_USE_EXTERNAL_CLOCK

Allowed Values

Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_MISC_PULL_CONTROL 0x21f0 uint16 0x0000

Bus-keeper/pull-disable for miscellaneous functions

This key configures the enhanced pull device control features present on some BlueCore chips for some miscellaneous input lines. See PSKEY_BCSP_PULL_CONTROL for more information on the pull device control features.

The modes selected by set bits in this key are enabled at boot time and never disabled.

Bit 0 controls "bus-keeper" mode for the reset pad: if this bit is clear (the default), "bus-keeper" mode is never enabled; if set, "bus-keeper" mode is enabled at the appropriate time by the firmware.

Bit 1 controls "pull-disable" mode for the reset pad: if this bit is clear (the default), the pull device is never disabled; if set, the pull device is disabled at the appropriate time by the firmware.

Bits 2 and 3 control the pull devices on the debugging SPI bus in a similar way.

Bits 4 and 5 control the pull devices on the LPC bus in a similar way.

Bit 6 is reserved.

Bit 7 controls "pull-disable" mode for the SPI/PCM select pad: if this bit is clear (the default), the pull device is never disabled; if set, the pull device is disabled at the appropriate time by the firmware.

Bit 8 is reserved.

Bit 9 controls "pull-disable" mode for the voltage regulator enable; if this bit is clear (the default), the pull device is never disabled; if set, the pull device is disabled during initialisation by the firmware. (Note that this line is connected to the reset line in some chips/packages.)

NOTE: not all of the pull controls are available on all chips.

WARNING: incorrect configuration of this key can lead to excessive power consumption and can potentially damage the chip. The default value is safe in this regard.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_DEEP_SLEEP_EXTERNAL_CLOCK_PULL_CONTROL 0x21f1 uint16 0x0000

Bus-keeper/pull-disable for external slow clock

This key configures the enhanced pull device control features present on some BlueCore chips for the external slow clock input. See PSKEY_BCSP_PULL_CONTROL for more information on the pull device control features.

The bits in this key only have any effect when an external slow clock is in use, as determined by PSKEY_DEEP_SLEEP_USE_EXTERNAL_CLOCK. The selected modes are enabled at boot time and never disabled.

Bit 0 controls "bus-keeper" mode: if this bit is clear (the default), "bus-keeper" mode is never enabled; if set, "bus-keeper" mode is enabled at the appropriate time by the firmware.

Bit 1 controls "pull-disable" mode: if this bit is clear (the default), the pull device is never disabled; if set, the pull device is disabled at the appropriate time by the firmware.

NOTE: incorrect configuration of this key can lead to excessive power consumption and can potentially damage the chip. The default value is safe in this regard.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_DSP0 0x2258 uint16[] none

User DSP configuration data 0

Keys PSKEY_DSP0 to PSKEY_DSP49 are for use by host and on-chip application- specific code to allocate as it chooses.

PSKEY_DSP0 to PSKEY_DSP24 may only be changed by DFU by placing them in the application protected section of the file and signing them with the application private key. These PSKeys are never incldued in DFU files uploaded from a BlueCore. This makes them suitable for storing module specific or sensitive information; use keys in the range PSKEY_DSP25 to PSKEY_DSP49 if such protection is not required.

Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_DEBUG_LOG_LEVEL 0x22b4 uint16 Default 2
Minimum 0
Maximum 5

Adjusts the level of internal log messages

This key permits adjustment of the level of logging for internal log messages. These log messages will be present in coredumps and may aid fault diagnosis by CSR.

Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_SC_PING_TIME_ADJUST 0x22b5 uint16 Default 0x0300
Minimum 0x0000
Maximum 0xffff

Adjustment for Secure Connections Ping Time

This key allows for adjustment to the firmware calculated lead time of how far in advance of the Authenticated Payload Timeout on a Secure Connection that a Ping packet should be sent to solicit a signed response from the peer device.

For Low Energy, this key value is used to compensate for over the air packets losses.

The key is expressed as a 16 bit fixed point number with 8 bits each side of the binary point. This gives the MS bit the value 128 and the LS bit the value 0.00390625 (that is 2 to the power -8).

The default value is 3.0, implies For BR/EDR: allow time for 3 attempts to ping. For Low Energy: Ping-point is calculated "3 * Connection Interval"
                ahead in time to compensate for over the air packet
                loss.


Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_BLE_MAX_REMOTE_MASTERS 0x22b6 uint16 Default 2
Minimum 0
Maximum 2

Maximum BLE remote masters

This PSKey holds the local device's maximum number of remote Bluetooth Low Energy (BLE) piconet masters.

Connecting to multiple Bluetooth Low Energy (BLE) remote masters implies the use of scatternets.

This pskey is limited by PSKEY_BLE_MAX_LINKS.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_LC_INQUIRY_PRIORITY 0x22c0 uint16 NORMAL_PRIORITY

Change BR/EDR inquiry and BLE scan priority

If set to 0 then inquiry and BLE scanning are scheduled at the normal priority level. If set to 1 then scheduling priority of BR/EDR inquiry and BLE scanning is lowered.

Note that both settings of this key can give undesirable performance in some circumstances. This key allows only a choice of which scenarios are affected. It is possible that with low priority level no inquiry or BLE scan results are received when doing a high speed file transfer. It is possible that at normal priority level, glitches are heard on a headset while doing inquiry.
  A BCCMD inquiry_priority is available to change the priority level between low and normal at runtime. This PSKey allows the priority level to be set at boot time.

Allowed Values
NORMAL_PRIORITY 0 inquiry and BLE scan scheduled at normal priority (0)
LOW_PRIORITY 1 inquiry and BLE scan scheduled at lowered priority (1)

Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_BLE_MAX_LINKS 0x22c2 uint16 Default 5
Minimum 0
Maximum 40

Maximum BLE links

The maximum number of concurrent BLE links to other devices.

The RAM used to maintain the connection state for a BLE link is shared with BR/EDR connections. Since PSKEY_MAX_ACLS determines the amount of RAM to allocate for BR/EDR connections, the value of PSKEY_BLE_MAX_LINKS should be less than or equal to PSKEY_MAX_ACLS.

It is suggested that this is only changed after consulting CSR.


Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_LC_GOLDEN_RANGE_MIN 0x22c3 int8 Default -60
Minimum -80
Maximum -56

Lower limit of the Bluetooth receiver golden range

This key controls the position of the lower limit of the Bluetooth receiver golden range. The upper limit is always 20 dB above the lower limit. This key is in units of dBm.

The golden range has two uses.

Firstly it's used in power control. If the signal being received from the remote device is above the upper limit of the golden range then BlueCore will signal the remote device to decrease its transmit power. If the signal is below the lower limit then BlueCore will signal the remote device to increase its transmit power.

Secondly it's used in the response to the HCI command Read_RSSI. If the received signal strength is above the top of the golden range the HCI command response is a positive number indicating how many decibels the signal was above the top. If the received signal strength is below the bottom of the golden range then the response is a negative number indicating how many decibels the signal is below the bottom. If the received signal is inside the golden range then the response is 0.

It is recommended that the value of this key not be changed from its default value of -60 dBm.

If you find your device has a golden range significantly different from the number given by this key then you may need to correct the RSSI calibration for the path loss of your module design. This is done by adjusting PSKEY_RSSI_CORRECTION.

Older firmware, depending on which chip it was targetting used either the keys PSKEY_LC_RSSI_GOLDEN_RANGE and PSKEY_PREFERRED_MIN_ATTENUATION or the key PSKEY_RSSI_PREFERRED_VALUES to determine the position of the golden range.

Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_BLE_DEFAULT_TX_POWER 0x22c8 int16 Default 10
Minimum -20
Maximum 10

Default transmit power

The BLE radio's default transmit power measured in dBm. The allowable range is from -20 dBm (0.01 mW) to 10 dBm (10 mW). The chip uses this for all transmitted BLE packets.

The firmware uses the highest value in the power table that is less than or equal to the requested default power.

Correct operation depends on the device having a valid power table - see PSKEY_LC_POWER_TABLE.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_ENABLE_SCO_STREAMS 0x22c9 bool FALSE

Unrouted SCO gives stream handles

This key determines the behaviour of unrouted SCO/eSCO connections. When this key is set to FALSE a SCO/eSCO connection with no routing will be routed to HCI. When this key is set to TRUE then a stream will be created and left for the host to connect later using the BCCMDs STREAM_GET_SOURCE/STREAM_GET_SINK and STREAM_CONNECT. In this latter case, version 25 firmware (but not versions 23 or 26) will send the SCO HCI handle and the stream identifiers to the host in an HQ_SCO_HANDLES message.

Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_DIG_MIC_0_PIOS 0x23d0 uint16 none

PIOs to be used for digital mic instance 0

This key defines which PIOs are used for the clock output to digital mic 0 and the data input from digital mic 0. Bits [7:0] specify the PIO used for the clock output and bits [15:8] the PIO used for the data input. The PIO chosen for the clock output must be an even numbered PIO. The PIO chosen for the data input must be an odd numbered PIO. A value of "NOT_MAPPED" (0xFF) can be when the pin is not required. Setting the key to 0xFFFF is equivalent to not having the PSKEY defined.

Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_DIGITAL_MIC_0_AMP_SEL 0x23d9 uint16 0x0700

Amplifier gain for the digital mic instance 0.

The lower 8 bits sets the LO_AMP_SEL and the higher 8 bits select the HI_AMP_SEL. The two values should be set to be symmetrical around the value of 3.5 (i.e. 0,7 or 1,6 or 2,5 or 3,4 or 4,3 or 5,2 or 6,1 or 7,0). Otherwise DC will appear at the codec output.

This key should only be changed on advice from CSR.

PSKEY_CODEC_OUT_DISABLE_WAITING_TIMEOUT 0x23df TIME 20 * SECOND

DAC disable waiting timeout

This PSKey specifies a timeout duration(in microseconds) that avoids repetitive pop and click noise that is generated when the DAC stream is repetitively connected and disconnected in a short span of time.

When the Host closes the DAC stream or disconnects the corresponding transform, the DAC is not turned off immediately. The DAC is turned off after a timeout period only if the Host does not use the same DAC channel again during this period.


Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_CODEC_PIO_SETUP_TIME 0x23e0 TIME Default 0x00000000
Minimum 0
Maximum 0xFFFFFFFF

Setup time for codec pio

This PSKey specifies the codec pio setup time(in microseconds), which is the delay between enabling the audio stream and enabling the codec pio line.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_BT_POWER_TABLE_V0 0x241a enhanced_power_setting[] {{51, 23, 0, 6, 0}, {34, 40, 0, 5, 0}, -20}, {{41, 23, 0, 5, 0}, {36, 40, 0, 4, 0}, -16}, {{44, 23, 0, 4, 0}, {35, 40, 0, 3, 0}, -12}, {{43, 23, 0, 3, 0}, {35, 40, 0, 2, 0}, -8}, {{25, 23, 0, 1, 0}, {34, 40, 0, 1, 0}, -4}, {{44, 23, 0, 1, 0}, {36, 40, 0, 0, 0}, 0}, {{47, 24, 0, 0, 0}, {50, 41, 0, 0, 0}, 4}, {{60,109, 0, 0, 0}, {59,109, 0, 0, 0}, 8}

Bluetooth radio power table

This table contains an array of entries which configures the chip for a given output power, under both BDR and EDR conditions. It supersedes PSKEY_LC_POWER_TABLE and PSKEY_LC_ENHANCED_POWER_TABLE.

The chip has an internal power amplifier (PA) which has a gain control. TX PA attenuators (tx_pa_atten) are present on BlueCore4 audio variants, BlueCore5 and later devices.

The power table stored under this PSKey provides a mapping between the gain settings of the various amplifiers and the corresponding transmit power. This table is the basis for all of the firmware's transmit power control: LMP dynamic power control, PSKEY_LC_MAX_TX_POWER, PSKEY_LC_DEFAULT_TX_POWER, etc.

Every module design must have an appropriate power table. The default value suits the CSR Casira hardware; this is not suitable for other module designs.

The PSKey's value is an array of "enhanced_power_setting" typed elements. The array's length is not fixed; typically an array is between 1 and 10 elements long.

The "enhanced_power_setting" type holds eight bytes within five uint16 words.

The first and second words control basic data rate (BDR) operation.

        1st uint16, lower byte: high 4 bits - TX mixer level for BDR.
                                low 4 bits - TX mixer offset for BDR.
        1st uint16, upper byte: uint8 internal_pa for BDR.
        2nd uint16, lower byte: bits 4 to 6 control the tx_pa_attn
                                value. Unused bits must be zero.
        2nd uint16, upper byte: This value must be zero.

The third and fourth words control enhanced data rate (EDR) operation. Their form mirrors that of the first and second words.

        3rd uint16, lower byte: high 4 bits - TX mixer level for EDR.
                                low 4 bits - TX mixer offset for EDR.
        3rd uint16, upper byte: uint8 internal_pa for EDR.
        4th uint16, lower byte: Bit 0 inhibits use of this power with
                                EDR (see below). Bit 1 inhibits use
                                of this power with BR (see below).
                                Bits 4 to 6 control the tx_pa_attn
                                value. Unused bits must be zero.
        4th uint16, upper byte: This value must be zero.

The fifth word specifies the output power - common to both data rates.

        5th uint16, lower byte: set to zero.
        5th uint16, upper byte: int8 tx dBm

As an example, the element { 0x0d12, 0x0000, 0x3f12, 0x0000, 0xf800 } specifies:

    To get power output -8 dBm for basic data rate (1 Mbps) use
        internal amp 13, TX mixer level 1, TX mixer offset 2.
    To get power output -8 dBm for enhanced data rate (2 or 3 Mbps)
        use internal amp 63, TX mixer level 1, TX mixer offset 2.

A power table is a list of these elements. The elements must be sequenced in ascending order of output power.

If the table contains only one element (five uint16s) then the firmware will use those settings for all power levels.

The firmware responds to peer requests to increase/decrease transmit power by stepping up and down this table. The Bluetooth specification constrains the sizes and number of steps, which in turn bounds the size and content of the power table.

In EDR operation, if the bottom bit of the fourth word is set, the power is marked as unavailable for EDR transmissions. Depending on the setting of BCCMD Limit_EDR_Power, the chip will either change the packet type table to basic rate; or refuse peer power control requests which request it to exceed the maximum allowed EDR power. If PSKEY_LC_DEFAULT_TX_POWER is greater than the maximum allowed EDR power, BlueCore will refuse to enter use EDR until the peer requests it to decrement its power sufficiently, after which it will attempt to change the packet type table to use EDR. If any of the powers is marked as unavailable for EDR transmissions an equal number of powers have to be marked as unavailable for BR transmissions by setting bit 1 of the fourth word. This is to make sure that while talking to devices that don't support enhanced power control (EPC), the power table has an equal number of power steps for both BR and EDR. Note: If the maximum transmit power has been modified via PSKEY_LC_MAX_TX_POWER or the VM trap VmTransmitPowerSetMaximum then care must be taken to ensure that the number of powers marked as unavailable for EDR transmissions is still equal to the number of powers marked as unavailable for BR transmissions.

See PSKEY_LC_POWER_TABLE, PSKEY_LC_MAX_TX_POWER, PSKEY_LC_DEFAULT_TX_POWER, PSKEY_LOCAL_SUPPORTED_FEATURES, PSKEY_TXRX_PIO_CONTROL, PSKEY_TX_AVOID_PA_CLASS1_PIO, PSKEY_TRANSMIT_OFFSET_CLASS1, PSKEY_TX_PRE_LVL_CLASS1, PSKEY_TX_OFFSET_HALF_MHZ, PSKEY_TRANSMIT_OFFSET, and PSKEY_TX_PRE_LVL.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_HOST_TX_SIGNAL_MODE 0x2433 uint16 0x0000

Specifies additional tx based signalling

This key can be set to cause BlueCore to signal its host transport transmit status via a PIO when using BCSP and H5.

Depending on the value selected BlueCore will either toggle a PIO after each packet is transmitted over the host interface, or will keep a PIO in one state (high or low) while data is being transmitted and then set the PIO to the other state once no more data is available to transmit.

The PIO is selected via PSKEY_HOST_TX_SIGNAL_PIO.

This functionality is only available when BCSP or H5 are selected as the transport and only in the BlueTooth stack not in the DFU loader.

Allowed Values
HOSTIO_TXSIGNAL_DISABLED 0 Disabled
HOSTIO_TXSIGNAL_PULSE_PIO 1 Pulse PIO at end of packet
HOSTIO_TXSIGNAL_ASSERT_PIO_HIGH 2 Assert PIO high until end of data
HOSTIO_TXSIGNAL_ASSERT_PIO_LOW 3 Assert PIO low until end of data

Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_HOSTIO_TBUS_USE_HCI_EXTN 0x2435 bool TRUE

Use hci_extn to route non-hci channels

Otherwise, they are routed via hci_extn, described in CSR document "BlueCore HCI Extensions", CS-101682-SP, available from the CSR support website.

If the system is using H4 or USB then these channels are always routed over hci_extn. For BCSP, this is controlled by PSKEY_HOSTIO_USE_HCI_EXTN.

Type bool is fundamentally a uint16 with values 0 and 1 mapping to FALSE and TRUE.

Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_CLOCK_STARTUP_DELAY_FINE_ADJUSTMENT 0x258d uint16 Default 4
Maximum 31

Additional clock startup delay in 1/32 ms

Adds finer granularity (1/32 ms) to PSKEY_CLOCK_STARTUP_DELAY. The total startup delay is (PSKEY_CLOCK_STARTUP_DELAY + PSKEY_CLOCK_STARTUP_DELAY_FINE_ADJUSTMENT/32) ms.

Notes:

 * the existing special case (PSKEY_CLOCK_STARTUP_DELAY=0 giving a
   delay of 5 ms) becomes PSKEY_CLOCK_STARTUP_DELAY=0 and
   PSKEY_CLOCK_STARTUP_DELAY_FINE_ADJUSTMENT=0, and still gives a
   delay of 5 ms.
 * whilst PSKEY_CLOCK_STARTUP_DELAY_FINE_ADJUSTMENT has units
   of 1/32 ms, current hardware restrictions mean that only 1/8 ms
   (rounded down) granularity is possible in practice.

Examples:

With PSKEY_CLOCK_STARTUP_DELAY=0, if PSKEY_CLOCK_STARTUP_DELAY_FINE_ADJUSTMENT is:

 * unset - delay 5 ms (special case, as before).
 * 12 - delay 0.375 ms (not recommended).

With PSKEY_CLOCK_STARTUP_DELAY=2 PSKEY_CLOCK_STARTUP_DELAY_FINE_ADJUSTMENT is:

 * 24 - delay 2.75 ms.
 * 25 - delay 2.75 ms.

 mask = 0x0028 # (1<<5 | 1<<3)

Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_ANA_FTRIM_OFFSET 0x2593 int16 Default 0
Minimum -300
Maximum 300

Trim offset to crystal frequency

This key specifies an offset to the crystal frequency specified in PSKEY_ANA_FREQ. The value is a signed 2's complement 16 bit integer which specifies the fractional part of the ratio between the true crystal frequency and the value in PSKEY_ANA_FREQ. This adjustment is intended to allow for small variations between individual crystals.

To calculate the value of the key, a measurement of an actual frequency is required.

Typically, a proxy for the crystal frequency is obtained by using the TXSTART radiotest (see "BCCMD Commands") to make the Bluetooth radio output a continuous wave at a specified frequency. Because the radio output frequency is proportional to the crystal frequency, the offset can be derived by comparing the radio frequency output when this key is zero (the default value) with the frequency you requested. The output radio frequency is usually measured with a spectrum analyser.

The value of this key is in parts per 2^20, so the correct offset is

((actual/requested) - 1) * 2^20

For example, if you requested a continuous wave at 2402 MHz and the output frequency with this key set to zero was 2402.0168 MHz, you would set this key to 7. If the output was 2401.9832 MHz, you would set this key to -7, value 0xfff9.

If you happen to measure the RF output frequency with this key set to a non-zero value, the calculated offset can simply be added to the current value of the key.

This key replaces PSKEY_ANA_FTRIM on some BlueCore7 parts. To determine whether you have such a part, either look at the PSKeys.txt or pskeys.html file released with the firmware (which only lists keys which are valid for that firmware) or connect PSTool to the chip (since PSTool only lists keys which the chip knows are valid).


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_SELECT_CLOCK_OUTPUT_PIO 0x2594 uint16 0xFFFF

Clock output PIO

This key specifies the clock output PIO pin number and can be set to any available PIO in the range 0-31 as follows -

If a frequency derived from the internal clock is to be used, set this to an even numbered PIO. If the XTAL frequency is to be used, set this to an odd numbered PIO.

Note that setting this key to the value 0xFFFF (the default value) or an invalid PIO number, disables the output.

See PSKEY_SELECT_CLOCK_OUTPUT_SOURCE to select the clock source. See PSKEY_SELECT_CLOCK_OUTPUT_RATE to select the output frequency derived from the internal clock.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_SELECT_CLOCK_OUTPUT_RATE 0x2595 uint16 0

Clock output rate

This key determines the output frequency for a clock derived from the internal clock. The output frequency will be 80MHz divided by the value of the key with an additional divide-by-2 (this ensures an even duty cycle). For example, a key value of 0x0001 will result in an output frequency of 40MHz, while 0x0002 yields 20MHz. The extra divide-by-2 can be switched off by setting Bit 15 of the key to 1. For example, 0x8001 yields 80MHz output, while 0x8002 results in 40MHz. This allows frequencies such as 16MHz to be selected. For values greater than 0x8001, the resulting output no longer has an even duty cycle, and the skewed mark:space ratio is approximately 1:(n-1), where n is the key value ignoring Bit 15, and n > 1.

Note Setting this key to the value 0 (the default value) disables clock output. This key has no effect if the XTAL frequency has been selected for output.

See PSKEY_SELECT_CLOCK_OUTPUT_SOURCE to select the clock source. See PSKEY_SELECT_CLOCK_OUTPUT_PIO to select the output PIO.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_XTAL_OSC_CONFIG 0x2596 uint16 2

Crystal oscillator config

Configures the crystal oscillator parameters on some parts.

Bits used:
 1,0: crystal oscillator capacitive loading in LP mode
 3,2: crystal oscillator capacitive loading in normal mode
  Where 00 is maximum capacitance and 11 the minimum in each 2 bit binary field. Also see PSKEY_LP_XTAL_LVL for LP mode.

You must consult the relevant documentation specific to ascertain what specific options are applicable to the part in use.

LP mode value should be greater than or equal to normal mode.
  It is suggested that this is only changed after consulting CSR

Note: On parts where this key is operative is it not intended for fine frequency tuning, it is only to establish reliable / low power operation. Frequency trimming is accomplished by using PSKEY_ANA_FTRIM_OFFSET

Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_SMPS_FREQ_OFFSET 0x25a0 int8 Default 0
Minimum -3
Maximum 3

SMPS frequency offset from 4MHz

This 8-bit key, if it exists, specifies an offset from the default switcher frequency for the SMPS's. The value is a signed 2's complement 8 bit integer, and is applied at power-up and is a single value for both SMPS's. In the chip, both SMPS's are clocked from the same source, which is a divided-down version of the 80MHz Dig PLL. This key simply modifies that division value from the default value of 9. This divided-down clock is only used for the SMPS's.

The frequency fed into both SMPS's is calculated as:

f = FdigPLL / (( DefaultDiv + 1 + PSKEY_SMPS_FREQ_OFFSET ) * 2 )

  where typically FdigPLL is 80MHz, and DefaultDiv = 9

So for a PSKEY_SMPS_FREQ_OFFSET = 0 the SMPS's are clocked at 4MHz

For example, if you wanted the switchers to run at 4.4444 MHz you would set this ket to -1, value 0xff. If you wanted 3.6363 MHz you would set this key to +1, value 0x01.

The MIN and MAX values keep the Freq in the range 3.07Mhz - 5.72 MHz This key should not be altered except on specific advice from CSR.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_CHARGER_EXT_MODE 0x25a1 bool FALSE

Charger Use External Transistor Mode

This key, when TRUE, specifies that external charger mode should be used. In external charger mode, the charge current passes through an external transistor and resistor. The value of the resistor sets the charge current and the transistor typically can pass a much larger current than the internal on-chip charger can supply.

This is an initial setting that can be overridden by a VM trap.

Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_CAP_SENSE_CALIBRATE 0x25b1 uint16 0

Cap Sense Calibrate

This key, when non-zero, calibrates the cap sense hardware against the stray capacitance of the product. It is reset to zero when calibration is complete. The calibration results are written to other PSKEYs, which are subsequently loaded each time the product powers up. For a successful calibration, the touch pads must not be touched or close to anything that may affect the capacitance of the pads.

To calibrate, use this key as a bit field of pads that are to be used in the product (and hence included in the calibration process). For example if the product uses pads 2-4, set this key to 0x1C and reboot the chip - calibration typically takes a few seconds. When using PSTool, it will succeed in reconnecting when the calibration process is complete.

If PSKEY_CAP_SENSE_SHIELD is TRUE, Bit 0 of this key is ignored.

Calibration results are stored to PSKEY_CAP_SENSE_BULK_CAP and PSKEY_CAP_SENSE_PRELOAD. PSKEY_CAP_SENSE_PRELOAD contains a value for each pad. A zero value indicates that the pad has not been calibrated. A complete set of zeros indicates that the calibration failed. This is likely because two pads have radically different capacitances and there is no single range the system can use that includes both values.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_CAP_SENSE_BULK_CAP 0x25b2 uint16 0

Cap Sense Bulk Capacitance

This key contains a calibration constant for the capacitive touch system.

It is written as a result of running a cap sense calibration (see PSKEY_CAP_SENSE_CALIBRATE) and contains a value determined by the physical layout of the capacitive touch sensors. It should not be manually altered except on advice from CSR.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_CAP_SENSE_PRELOAD 0x25b3 uint16[] 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0

Cap Sense Preload Values

This key contains calibration constants for each touch pad in the capacitive touch system. A zero value indicates that the pad has not been calibrated. A complete set of zeros indicates that the calibration failed.

It is written as a result of running a cap sense calibration (see PSKEY_CAP_SENSE_CALIBRATE) and contains values determined by the physical layout of the capacitive touch sensors. It should not be manually altered except on advice from CSR.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting

Cap Sense Analogue Shield

This key, when TRUE, enables the cap sense analogue shield function on pad 0. In this state, pad 0 becomes an output and cannot be used as a touch pad.

When FALSE, the analogue shield function is disabled and pad 0 can be used as a touch pad.

Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting

Select handler for USB suspend request

This key specifies if the firmware or VM application should handle bus powered USB suspend requests. The behaviour
  If set TRUE, bus powered USB suspend requests will be passed to VM. If set FALSE, bus powered USB suspend requests will be handled by the firmware. The firmware will disable the charger and enter deep-sleep.

Allowed Values
TRUE 1 Enabled
FALSE 0 Disabled

Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_ENABLE_SOFT_WD 0x25c0 bool FALSE

Enable watchdog's soft/debug mode

This key is intended as debug aid to find background-lockup problems after the watchdog has been disabled by the test systems.

When FALSE, the watchdog works normally.

When TRUE, it is treated as a "soft" watchdog, in the sense that it does not cause the chip to reset even when fired. The exact mechanism differs between pre-BlueCore7 chips and BlueCore7+:

On pre-BlueCore7 (pre-Jemima) chips, if this key is set to TRUE and watchdog is disabled (by setting PSKEY_WD_TIMEOUT = 0), the watchdog kicks will continue to be scheduled as usual every PSKEY_WD_PERIOD. But instead of kicking the hardware, it will take a timestamp and compare it with the last such timestamp. A difference of more than twice of PSKEY_WD_PERIOD will cause a fault to be raised (FAULT_WATCHDOG_KICK_TOO_LATE), which may be converted to a panic by setting PSKEY_PANIC_ON_FAULT. Note that PSKEY_WD_TIMEOUT should be 0 to enable this soft mode. If PSKEY_WD_TIMEOUT != 0, this key is ignored and the watchdog is active.

On BlueCore7 onwards, if this key is set to TRUE the watchdog will fire if timeout happens. However it will only halt the chip, not cause a reset. This is actually a special mode of the watchdog, unlike the previous case where it was purely a software mechanism. Note that in this case, PSKEY_WD_TIMEOUT should be nonzero to enable this mode. If PSKEY_WD_TIMEOUT == 0, this key is ignored and the watchdog is disabled.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_VREG_EN_REROUTE_INTERNALLY_VIA_PIO 0x25c1 uint16 8

Internal PIO used for VREG_EN wakeup signal

On CSR-8670, if we require edge-triggered wakeups on the VREG_EN input pin we must internally dedicate a PIO for this.

This PIO will then not be available for any other use. Only PIO0-15 are available for use in this way. A value of 0xffff indicates that no internal PIO routing will take place and there will be no VREG_EN wakeup event from deep sleep.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_VCHG_REROUTE_INTERNALLY_VIA_PIO 0x25c2 uint16 9

Internal PIO used for VCHG wakeup signal

On CSR-8670, if we require edge-triggered wakeups on the VCHG input pin we must internally dedicate a PIO for this.

This PIO will then not be available for any other use. Only PIO0-15 are available for use in this way. A value of 0xffff indicates that no internal PIO routing will take place and there will be no VCHG wakeup event from deep sleep.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting

Crystal pullability

Defines the pullability of crystal in low power mode. It is measured in ppm/pF i.e. change in the ppm accuracy for each pF reduction in capacitance. This value is normally found in Crystal's datasheet.

It is suggested that this is only changed after consulting CSR


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_SPI_CONFIG 0x25c4 uint32 0

Spi bus config

Define the spi bus configuration. This PSKey only configures the behavior of hald duplex spi transfer. Some device running on full duplex spi, for example spi-flash, will not be affected by this PSKey. BIT 0 - 7: WRITE speed of half duplex spi
              0x00 -- fastest speed firmware supports
              0xFF -- slowest speed firmware supports BIT 8 - 15: READ speed of half duplex spi
              0x00 -- fastest speed firmware supports
              0xFF -- slowest speed firmware supports BIT 16 - 31 SPI device feature
              SPI -- EEPROM ------> page size in bytes


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_SERIAL_FLASH_ENABLE 0x25d8 bool TRUE

Enable Serial Flash

This key controls whether serial flash is enabled and probed for at boot time.

If set to Always, the firmware will always probe for serial flash.

If set to Only to probe for PS, the firmware will only probe for serial flash if it selects serial flash as a candidate for Persistent Store.

Consult your datasheet or firmware release note for information on how your firmware chooses where to search for Persistent Store.

Allowed Values
TRUE 1 Always
FALSE 0 Only to probe for PS

Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_FSTAB 0x25e6 uint16[] 0x0000

File System Table

This PSKEY sets the priority order of the union file system and what file systems are mounted. The first entry in the array has the highest priority. Each 16 bit entry is encoded as follows:

xxDD CFxx PPPP PPPP

Where:
    D - Physical device: 0 = internal memory, 1 = SQIF
    C - Command flag
    F - Fault flag
    P - Partition number or command id
    x - Reserved and must be 0.

If the command flag is set P is a command id, else it is a partition number. Partition number can only be 0 for internal memory and 0 to 255 for SQIF. A fault is recorded if the partition fails to mount and the fault flag is set.

Command Ids:
    0 = The lowest numbered partition on the specified device that
        contains a file system is mounted.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting

This key determines the maximum number of advertisement's RSSI filtering entries.

Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_ENABLE_SCATTERNET_ESCO_DRIFT_COMP 0x25fb bool FALSE

Enable scatternet SCO clock drift compensation

In a scatternet scenario where we have SCO/eSCO links both as master and slave there can be dropouts in (e)SCO audio due to DeSCO renegotiation as the slot clocks of the two master devices drift and the reserved slots coincide.

Enabling this key allows the BlueCore firmware to implement a feature that compensates this drift so that the reserved slots do not clash.

Allowed Values
TRUE 1 Enabled
FALSE 0 Disabled

Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_ENABLE_TX_IF_REDUCTION 0x2602 bool TRUE

Reduce the radio's transmit IF

This key modifies the behaviour of the radios selection of transmit intermediate frequencies on devices where the Tx IFs are set by: PSKEY_TX_OFFSET_HALF_MHZ PSKEY_MR_TX_OFFSET_HALF_MHZ PSKEY_CLASS1_TX_OFFSET_HALF_MHZ PSKEY_MR_CLASS1_TX_OFFSET_HALF_MHZ

Any of the above with an offset of +1 or -1 will request that a +/- 0.5 MHz IF is used for the appropriate transmission. If this key has been enabled those 0.5 MHz IF frequencies will be reduced to 0.375 MHz, if it is disabled they remain at 0.5 MHz.

Note: The sign of resulting frequency offset may vary between different parts and also for other reasons, the reduction will work as expected in either case. Other configured IF frequencies will not be reduced by this feature, even if enabled.

This, and the above keys, should only be changed on advice from CSR.


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting

Enables accurate rate detection in SPDIF

When enabled SPDIF receiver expects incoming signal to be accurate and only variance of +/- 0.4% will be allowed. Disabling this PS key will allow a variance of +/ -1%.

Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_VM_PANIC_DBG_INFO_LEVEL 0x270c uint16 0

Level of storing debug info on VM panic

This PSKEY is used to specify the level of debug information to be stored in the debug info PS keys (PSKEY_VM_PANIC_DBG_INFO_BASIC and PSKEY_VM_PANIC_DBG_INFO_APP_STACK) in the event of VM application panic. The valid levels are:

0 (Disabled) - No debug information will be stored.

1 (Debug Info Basic) - Basic VM/DSP debug information will be stored into PSKEY_VM_PANIC_DBG_INFO_BASIC (please refer its description for more details).

2 (Debug Info Extended) - Basic VM/DSP debug information and VM stack trace (upto 64 words) will be stored into PSKEY_VM_PANIC_DBG_INFO_BASIC and PSKEY_VM_PANIC_DBG_INFO_APP_STACK respectively.

Allowed Values
0 Disabled
1 Debug Info Basic
2 Debug Info Extended (Basic + VM stack)

Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_VM_PANIC_DBG_INFO_BASIC 0x270d uint16[] none

Storage for basic debug info on VM panic

If PSKEY_VM_PANIC_DBG_INFO_LEVEL is set to "Debug Info Basic" or "Debug Info Extended", this PS Key will be used to store basic debug information after a VM application panic. The debug information are stored in the following order: 1. Version Number (1 word, MSW) 2. Panic code (1 word) 3. Panic context (1 word) 4. VM application start address (2 words) 5. VM context registers - AH (1W), AL (1W), UXH (1W), UX (1W),
                          UY (1W)), PC (2W) (total 7 words) 6. Bitmap of allocated VM slots (4 words) 7. DSP application start address (2 words) 8. DSP PC (2 words) 9. DSP RT-link register (2 words, LSW)


Key Name Key Number Type Default Setting
PSKEY_VM_PANIC_DBG_INFO_APP_STACK 0x270e uint16[] none

Storage for VM stack on VM panic

If PSKEY_VM_PANIC_DBG_INFO_LEVEL is set to "Debug Info Extended",this PS Key will be used to store VM stack (max 64 words from current stack pointer location) after a VM application panic.

Key Name Key Number Type Values
PSKEY_I2C_TRANSFER_TIME_THRESHOLD 0x2736 TIME Default 50 * MILLISECOND
Minimum 15 * MILLISECOND
Maximum 500 * MILLISECOND

I2C transfer time threshold (microseconds)

Clock stretching by the slave device causes to increase the time needed for an I2C transfer. This eventually affects the overall system performance. This pskey configures the threshold time (in microseconds) within which an I2C transfer is expected to complete. If time taken for an I2C transfer exceeds this limit, firmware will raise FAULT_I2C_TRANSFER_OVER_STRETCHED.

It is adviced not to alter this PSKey without analyzing the impact on the system performance.
